@Article{Rondelli.etal2013,
  author    = {Rondelli, Bernardo and Stride, Sebastian and {Garc{\'i}a-Granero}, Juan Jos{\'e}},
  journal   = {Journal of Cultural Heritage},
  title     = {Soviet {{Military Maps}} and {{Archaeological Survey}} in the {{Samarkand}} {{Region}}},
  year      = {2013},
  issn      = {1296-2074},
  month     = may,
  note      = {\section{Annotazioni\\ (6/6/2022, 14:38:28)} \par "In this paper, we present an underexploited type of remote sensing data for systematic survey and archaeological heritage management in Central Asia and throughout the former Soviet Union: 1:10,000 Soviet military maps of the 1950s. We argue that their precision and the early date at which they were produced make it possible to employ them as a reference tool for systematic archaeological survey and management." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 270) \par "In Central Asia, like in other parts of the world, the introduction of mechanised farming and the transformation of the landscape caused by agricultural intensification over the last 50 years have resulted in a massive destruction of archaeological remains" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 270) \par "However, the precise impact of this destruction has not yet been quantified and evaluated in a diachronic perspective. That is to say, information about the state of preservation of a few important monuments and archaeological mounds is available, but the number of mounds totally destroyed in the last 50 years is unknown. This lack of knowledge is a major problem, both for the study of settlement patterns and quantitative analysis, as well as for the planning of archaeological heritage management." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 270) \par "The majority of ``archaeological sites'' in Central Asia are earthen mounds (often referred to as tepa/e or depe), which result from the stratigraphic accumulation of anthropic layers." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 270) \par "In Central Asia, Soviet agricultural development programs started in the late 1950s (precise dates vary from region to region) [2]. This led to a dramatic transformation in land use and the consequent wholesale destruction of the traditional landscapes to make way for large, perfectly horizontal, irrigated cotton fields [3]. It was made possible by the mechanisation of agricultural production in the Soviet Union, with a rise in the number of agricultural machinery from less than 1.5 million in 1940 and 1950 (with the vast majority in the European part), to 2.5 million in 1960 and over 3 million in 1965 [4] (the same trend can be observed in Central Asia but with a later starting date [5]). These earth moving machines enabled the large scale destruction of topographical anomalies, most of which corresponded to archaeological mounds." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 271) \par "During this period, traditional means of destruction of archaeological mounds were exacerbated whereas reasons for preservation lost ground. For instance, the production of bricks was centralised in specific locations and trucks were sent out to topographical anomalies to obtain raw material. Furthermore, sacred landscapes (involving both graves and legends, which led to the preservation of numerous mounds) were swept aside by the transformation of society and population displacement." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 271) \par "The rising consciousness of the destruction of archaeological heritage, as well as the large scale modification of the landscape explain the growing emphasis on the use of historical satellite imagery such as CORONA imagery [7,8] within archaeological research programs in different regions of Central Asia [9\textendash 14]. CORONA imagery is a powerful resource to study land use changes and to detect past anthropic remains, such as palaeochannels, field systems and roads [15]. However, the extraction of the precise coordinates of the archaeological mounds identified in the CORONA involves a time consuming process of orthorectification and geocorrection [8,16,17]." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 271) \par "All the maps were based upon aerial photography and field survey. The geographic projection of the maps is Gauss-Kruger, datum Pulkovo 1942. The network of ground control points was partially adjusted by photo-triangulation, but mostly based on the result of fieldwork. The project was run by the military with such accuracy that topographical errors were considered equivalent to high treason, thus ensuring the quality of the work undertaken (personal communication G. Fedorenko, National Institute of Geodesy and Cartography, Tashkent, Uzbekistan)." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 272) \par "Following the collapse of the Soviet Union in the early 1990s, some of these maps became available for a short period of time, and various foreign teams working in Central Asia started collaborative projects in the context of which they were able to consult these maps [12,28,29]. Today, 50 years after their production, these maps are no longer under copyright, and a few of them are now downloadable or purchasable from the internet (e.g., http://sovietmaps.com/; http://en.poehali.org/maps \textendash{} last accessed 18/10/2011)." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 272) \par "Although mapping archaeological mounds was not one of the tasks of the Soviet Military Topographic Service, the parameters selected resulted in the systematic recording of archaeological mounds. If we check the legends of the Soviet military maps [30] we find specific categories identifying the topographical anomalies considered here such as burial mound and tailings pile (drawn to scale!) (Fig. 1). This demonstrates that Soviet topographers were often aware that many of the mounds that they recorded were archaeological sites (information confirmed by personal communication G. Fedorenko, Institute of National Geodesy, Tashkent, Uzbekistan). Indeed, occasionally, the topographers themselves found archaeological remains during the installation of geodetic bases on the top of the mound and reported this information to the local authorities responsible for archaeological heritage management" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 272) \par "Furthermore, cartographers also included many other special features within the cultural landscape, including cattle enclosures, every single tomb, yurt (nomadic tent), wall and cave, but also chapels, mosques, Buddhist lamaseries and temples (in some case drawn to scale), as well as single isolated trees. The maps also record local place names, particularly useful because much of the original names are now forgotten due to repeated changes, which took place both during the Soviet period and since." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 272) \par "The correspondence between topographical anomalies and archaeological mounds is true not only for large topographical anomalies but also for very small ones \textendash{} in certain cases the maps record ``mounds'' of less than 50 cm in height and 5 m" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 272) \par "The shape of the anomaly is often precisely recorded with contour lines every 1 m, sometimes every 0.5 m, and specific indications of 0.1 m in precision. The quality of the maps is such that it is possible to compare details from them with topographical plans of archaeological mounds made by archaeological teams (Figs. 2 and 3). Indeed, in some cases we suspect that the archaeologist/topographer had access to an extract from the map, which he simply copied" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 273) \par "we superimposed the coordinate of the mounds detected from Soviet military maps to recent Google Earth imagery, and using GPS waypoints, we were able to identify the best route to reach each mound [12,34,35]" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 274) \par "The predominance of earthen architecture in Central Asia means that any structure built by humans will give rise, after abandonment, to a mound. Because the cartographers mapped all topographical anomalies, we may confidently postulate that Soviet maps are excellent sources: \textbullet{} to remotely detect archaeological mounds; \textbullet{} to define a field survey in order to validate these remote detections; \textbullet{} to infer the level of destruction of archaeological mounds by comparing these maps with more recent sources such as satellite imagery" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 275) \par "This article shows an underestimated destruction of archaeological mounds over the past 50 years; however, an exhaustive research and debate on the causes and trends of this loss is still needed. For that reason, a study of the relationship between land use change and archaeological mound destruction is now in progress. The comparison between Soviet military maps, historical satellite imagery (CORONA, Landsat) and more recent ones (ASTER, IKONOS, QuickBird) will lead to the recording of the different stages of landscape change and archaeological heritage destruction. This analytical approach will support a model building of risk management [37,38]." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 275) \par "In a moment of important changes and reforms in land use planning in Uzbekistan and in Central Asia in general, the aim is to provide a model for a more sustainable development, which takes into account the archaeological heritage" (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 275) \par "F.A. Shibanov, The essence and content of the history of cartography and the results of fifty years of work by soviet scholars, Cartographica: The International Journal for Geographic Information and Geovisualization 12 (1975) 141\textendash 145." (Rondelli et al., 2013, p. 275)},
