  note       = {\section{Annotazioni\\ (11/7/2022, 09:54:46)} \par "Origins Although characterisation of landscape and types of place has been undertaken since the nineteenth century (Herring 2016,14\textendash 15), the form known as HLC was developed, quite rapidly, under the eye of English Heritage (as Historic England then was), and that of Graham Fairclough in particular, in the early 1990s, now a generation ago. Its overtly inclusive and comprehensive approach and principles were drawn from the heritage and landscape preoccupations of their time. Archaeologists and planners were recognising that landscape was boundless and singular, that all of it had history and was meaningful (Countryside Commission 1994; Fairclough et al. 1999), and all was capable of being valued and thoughtfully managed: `all landscape matters', rather than `some landscapes matter'" (Herring, 2020, p. 114) \par "hey examined and explored the possibilities surrounding the more inclusive and holistic view of landscape, primarily through the 1992\textendash 1994 historic landscape project undertaken by Oxford Archaeology Unit and Cobhams, reported on in Yesterday's World, Tomorrow's Landscape" (Herring, 2020, p. 114) \par "This concentrated on developing means of better understanding the past's contribution to present (and future) landscape character" (Herring, 2020, p. 114) \par "he sum of the historical, ecological, scenic and emotional values of the countryside' (Countryside Commission 1994, 4), in order to guide better management and decision-making about change." (Herring, 2020, p. 115) \par "The method of HLC is classically archaeological in depending on typology. It identifies and interprets HLC Types via distinctive attributes as seen in comprehensive and systematic sources, mostly area-wide mapping (current and historic) or complete aerial photography coverage. Particular places whose attributes and qualities mean they Figure 2. Ramsgate in Kent contains urban landscape of character and value even where individual structures and features are modern, damaged and commonplace (Photo: Pete Herring). LANDSCAPES 11" (Herring, 2020, p. 115) \par "coalesce as blocks of landscape that share a predominant historical character are mapped as polygons and assigned to types, usually represented by different colours and shadings." (Herring, 2020, p. 116) \par "When extended to the remainder of Cornwall in 1994 (Figure 4), HLC was applied to parts that were less well understood, but which still had distinguishable historical attributes visible on comprehensive and consistent sources: the patterns visible in field systems, industrial complexes, open ground, urban areas, and so on. The HLC for Cornwall (Figure 5) became an initial spatial framework of the then current understanding of the landscape's character and development, a framework in which people could design research to test and improve that understanding, judge the landscape's historical significance, and make more informed decisions about its future." (Herring, 2020, p. 116) \par "Those two pilot HLCs were commissioned primarily to inform Landscape Character Assessments (LCAs) of Bodmin Moor (Land Use Consultants 1994) and Cornwall (Landscape Design Associates 1994), but they were also designed with other applications or aims in mind (Herring 1998). . To provide all decision-makers with an evidenced understanding of landscape's origins and development, expressed in the HLC mapping and in the descriptive and interpretative text, statistics and time-depth matrices (Figure 6) prepared for each HLC Type, and in the summary landscape histories of Bodmin Moor and Cornwall drawn from and supported by the HLCs. . To use knowledge of origins and development to suggest what other attributes, including below-ground remains, may be expected within HLC Types, and thereby inform archaeological decision-making when considering change. . To assess the significance of HLC Types in relation to the ways they may be affected by certain types of change and thereby assess sensitivity to (or capacity for) those types of change and thus contribute to establishing the form and design of future landscape. . To improve understanding of landscape development by designing research that fills gaps. . To support constructive working partnerships between the heritage sector and those with different interests in landscape \textendash{} natural, cultural, economic, political, etc." (Herring, 2020, p. 116) \par "The Cornwall HLC has text (Herring 2009b) for each Type organised by these subsections. . Defining attributes that distinguish the Type from others. . Principal historical processes, with emphasis on those that have influenced surviving historical or semi-natural features." (Herring, 2020, p. 116) \par "Typical historical and archaeological components, including types of heritage assets and semi-natural habitats typical or distinctive of the Type. . Principal locations in Cornwall. . Variability in aspects of the Type across Cornwall. . Past interaction with other types, and the ways they contribute to a holistic understanding of Cornwall's historic landscape. . Heritage values, as expressed through the four values introduced in Conservation Principles (English Heritage 2008). These allow discussion of the range of perceptions diverse communities may have of each Type. {$\bigcirc$} Aesthetic value {$\bigcirc$} Communal value {$\bigcirc$} Evidential value {$\bigcirc$} Historical value . Potential for amenity and education, based on the likely interest visitors and educators may find in the Type. . Survival, a summary of the typical condition of both the Type and its components in Cornwall." (Herring, 2020, p. 117) \par "Vulnerability, combining a summary of any statutory protection change that this Type typically receives, and its sensitivity to various forms of change. . Forces for change, summarising long and medium-term opportunities and threats from development, land use, changes in attitudes, etc. . Safeguarding the Type, including brief thoughts on ways to sustainably counter threats and take advantage of opportunities that will conserve and reinforce historical character." (Herring, 2020, p. 118) \par "HLCs have been deepened where appropriate or required, usually in smaller areas affected by particular opportunities or threats. In Cornwall, finer-grained characterisation of the catchment area of the River Lynher concentrated on illustrating changes in land uses in the last 170 years to inform a project aimed at improving understanding of agricultural impacts on the river's water quality. It looked more closely at the variety in field patterns and the different historic agricultural regimes they reflected (Herring and Tapper 2002). Another project considered changes in rough ground vegetation and land use on the north Cornish Atlantic coast over the same period, when many cliffs and steep valley sides that were once grazed in the summer months had been gradually abandoned, in order to evaluate the potential for adjusting vegetation cover again to prepare for reintroduction of the Large Blue, a highly valued butterfly" (Herring, 2020, p. 121)},
