  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (14/5/2022, 21:45:11)} \par "Historic Landscape Characterisation (HLC) offers the opportunity to identify the traces of past spatial organisation through remote sensing and comprehensive aerial mapping. Furthermore, the method can be used to study towns, villages and rural structure in a comparable manner, rather than focussing solely on the coniguration of extra-urban areas." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=9}{Wordsworth 2018:153}) \par "In the United Kingdom, archaeological practitioners are familiar with the need to see beyond the regularly parcelled pastures of the early modern period to trace the fragments of earlier systems. The science of delineating this evidence comes under the rubric of 'Historic Landscape Characterisation' (HLC)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=9}{Wordsworth 2018:153}) \par "Just as the history of rural landscapes can be read through the vestiges of former ield boundaries and stream courses, it is unusual for a town with historical roots to lose all traces of its pre-modern urban fabric." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=12}{Wordsworth 2018:156}) \par "Fig. 2 presents data taken from a snapshot of the town in 1970, provided by Corona satellite imagery.18 The urban area of B{$\Elzschwa$}rd{$\Elzschwa$} to the north of the T{$\Elzschwa$}rt{$\Elzschwa$}r\c{c}ay represents an area of some 268ha, less than half its present extent (546ha), owing to the rapid expansion of the town in the 1980s and 1990s. At the time of the aerial photograph, seemingly very little had been attempted in terms of formalising the urban layout and, while the streets conform roughly to a grid plan, the primary axes are not rigidly laid out, but they are present throughout the core of the town. While it is not possible to state with certainty at the present time how old this pattern of streets is, there is no reason to suppose that it does not relate to the pre-modern period" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=13}{Wordsworth 2018:157}) \par "Individual 'neighbourhoods' in the residential parts of the town of 1970 show a more irregular layout - their dendritic structure ending in a series of cul-de-sacs" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=13}{Wordsworth 2018:157}) \par "A further advantage of using imagery from the recent past is being able to evaluate the impact of development within the urban area. While in cities with better documentation a full historical map-regression exercise would be a preferable starting point for archaeological investigations, the resources for such an endeavour are unavailable for Bardha\lasp a. It is possible, however, to identify some areas that have remained continuously 'open ground' from before the 1970s imagery was obtained and to investigate whether these zones may represent archaeological potential." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=13}{Wordsworth 2018:157}) \par "The application of HLC for cityscapes, while rapidly being adopted in the United Kingdom, is challenging in these circumstances, based on the resolution of the data available" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=14}{Wordsworth 2018:158}) \par "Meanwhile, analysing the landscape of B{$\Elzschwa$}rd{$\Elzschwa$} at a broader scale can situate the historical city within its immediate hinterland" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=14}{Wordsworth 2018:158}) \par "When categorising the rural zone around the town with basic HLC classes (analogous to those systems developed in British examples), there are some zones that have direct parallels and can easily be delineated in a similar way. Both woodlands and urban areas (see above) are straightforwardly traceable on the aerial imagery and, on a subtler level, the satellite photography reveals the remains of current and relict water channels" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=14}{Wordsworth 2018:158}) \par "Woodland areas are easily categorised from the Corona imagery, appearing almost black with the dark green of the canopy." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=14}{Wordsworth 2018:158}) \par "Documentary sources from the medieval period onwards suggest that a substantial portion of the region was previously wooded, far more than is represented by these isolated stands" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=14}{Wordsworth 2018:158}) \par "The remains of both relict and active water channels are somewhat easier to detect, appearing as dark linear features across the landscape" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=14}{Wordsworth 2018:158}) \par "Turning to the land use, it is apparent from the discussion above that deining a 'system of ields', the basis for much of the analogous work in UK HLC, requires a more locally applicable labelling, as the visible palimpsest does not suggest large open-area cultivation." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=16}{Wordsworth 2018:160}) \par "On the basis of the Corona image, it is possible to divide the open ground into two categories, simply on the basis of relected tone in the greyscale photograph. The perceived difference is one of vegetation density, as the 'greener' areas relect a darker signature in the image, broadly speaking." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=16}{Wordsworth 2018:160}) \par "Returning to the Historic Landscape Characterisation plot, these unirrigated areas visible on the satellite imagery are seemingly the relics of this system, the substantially pastoralist economy, prior to widespread ield creation." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=17}{Wordsworth 2018:161}) \par "A different pattern of land use can be seen in some limited zones to the north-east of the town, where small relict linear ield boundaries are visible as pale lines in an area that is darker overall than the zone described above. It would appear then that irrigated agriculture can be conirmed in the immediate vicinity of the urban area, and indeed similar signatures can be found around the boundaries of several of the nearby villages but are small in number and poorly deined." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=17}{Wordsworth 2018:161}) \par "The same map data from the irst half of the 20\textsuperscript{th} century also corroborates that some of the land is designated pastureland. Small structures, labelled Nomadenlager (nomad camps) pepper the spaces in between named villages." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=17}{Wordsworth 2018:161}) \par "Most of the wide-coverage late Soviet cartography from the second half of the 20\textsuperscript{th} century is now publically available,28 but although charts at 1:50,000 scale and larger were almost certainly made, the only format that has been retrieved is at 1:100,000" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=18}{Wordsworth 2018:162}) \par "There are several interesting features included on these more detailed, topographic maps including basic land categories, and water channels, still active when the chart was produced. Given that it was printed in 1985, however, its main usefulness is in broadly conirming features identiied on the Corona imagery in the period of the expansion of the irrigation system." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=18}{Wordsworth 2018:162}) \par "In order to further deine the character of the land types being observed remotely and investigate the chronology of their occupation, it has been possible to undertake a limited amount of ieldwalking in the region around the town" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JJ36UT8Y?page=18}{Wordsworth 2018:162}) \par "On a very general level, the ground-truthing exercise conirmed that the extensive terraforming of the Soviet period has almost entirely obliterated the distinction between the two landscape types