@Book{David.Thomas2008,
  editor    = {David, Bruno and Thomas, Julian},
  publisher = {{Left Coast Press}},
  title     = {Handbook of {{Landscape Archaeology}}},
  year      = {2008},
  address   = {{Walnut Creek, CA}},
  isbn      = {978-1-59874-294-7},
  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (14/2/2022, 15:01:11)} \par "Landscape archaeology is today an outstandingly vibrant aspect of the discipline, because it brings together a series of quite distinct traditions of thought and practice, but these are by no means reconciled to a common set of objectives or approaches" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "For many decades, landscape has provided archaeologists with a framework for contextualizing observations and establishing relations and parallels between sites of a particular period. Moreover, it presents the opportunity for diachronic investigations, in which the changing use and inhabitation of a particular region are the focus" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "the scale of analysis" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "landscape can also be understood as an aggregation of resources, affording both opportunities and limitations for human development." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "spatial relationships among people, soils, raw materials, and water sources that demand attention." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "More recently, a philosophical concern with landscape has become infl uential, with the recognition" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "that the lived world is not simply a backdrop to everyday action but integral to all human activity" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "Historically, concerns with space and landscape have appeared on the archaeological agenda at times when difference, variability, and plurality have been at issue." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par "here are regional and national differences in the ways in which archaeologists seek to put their evidence into a landscape setting\textemdash or, in some cases, decline to do so" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=26}{David and Thomas 2008:26}) \par ""Landscape archaeology" does not have a particularly long history. It was perhaps fi rst used by Mick Aston and Trevor Rowley in the mid-1970s (Aston and Rowley 1974), but it was only in the midto late-1980s that it began to be widely cited in academic work. This is not to say that archaeologists have not long employed notions of "landscape" (see Darvill, this volume). But it is arguable that during the 1970s and 1980s "landscape" ceased to be simply a unit of analysis over and above the "site" and became instead an object of investigation in its own right." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=28}{David and Thomas 2008:28}) \par "what archaeologists have understood to be "landscape archaeology" has shifted, so that today it does not mean exactly what it used to even 20 years ago" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "Nor is it presently employed in quite the same way by everyone (see below)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "Indeed, even within the works of individual archaeologists, the term may shift its connotation according to context." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "We direct the reader to chapters in this volume by Darvill, Patterson, and McIntosh for histories of landscape archaeology in various parts of the world." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "The focus was then fi rmly on human impacts on and interactions with their physical surroundings" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "We thus have during these early years, and on both sides of the Atlantic and beyond, a number of infl uential works all aiming to address past human historical landscapes as environmental archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "With such a focus on relationships between people and their physical environments came ongoing calls to more accurately and systematically characterize the way people occupied and used places in the past" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "T" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "his meant refi nements in fi eld methodologies and statistical analyses, in particular as they relate to the distribution of archaeological materials and sites across the landscape." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "It also led to a more detailed understanding of landscape formation processes" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "innovative analytical techniques were required." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "What was also necessary was a new spatial scale of approach, one that targeted relatively small and well-defi ned regions. The results were major developments in survey methodologies" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "simulation and predictive modeling" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "taphonomy" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "geoarchaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "and bioarchaeology and palaeoecology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=29}{David and Thomas 2008:29}) \par "each of these specialist developments had deeper historical roots" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "Many of these developments were closely associated with an increasing sophistication of statistical procedures" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "In this context, both in the United Kingdom and in the United States there emerged schools of thought that systematically sought to access past spatial patterning of settlements and cultural objects across landscapes" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "One key development in the United States was a differentiation by Winters" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "of the terms settlement pattern (the spatial distribution of sites) and settlement system (the way that people organized themselves in the landscape)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "These now-disaggregated concepts quickly took hold throughout much of the English-speaking archaeological world. However, they remained most infl uential in the United States, where the processual interests of the New Archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "targeted settlement systems" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "for their ability to inform on an "archaeology of place" that was reduced largely to relationships between settlement" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "and subsistence" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "By focusing on settlement systems rather than settlement patterns in and for themselves, archaeological attention in the United States thus quickly turned to process rather than location of human behavior in the landscape." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "Such differentiation of what are essentially economically (and largely subsistence-) driven mobility strategies aimed to distinguish among various forms of organizational alternatives in specifi c environmental settings so as to better model evolutionary pathways under changing environmental conditions." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "Thus, "since systems of adaptation are energy-capturing systems, the strategies that they employ must bear some relationship to the energy or, more important, the entrophy structure of the environments in which they seek energy"" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "In the United Kingdom, however, archaeological interest took what initially looked like a minor turn in a different direction aimed more at characterizing the spatial patterning of archaeological sites and artifacts, an originally potentially insignifi cant turn that eventually led to what could be described as a paradigmatic shift" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par "The 1970s into the 1980s also saw the rapid development of various multidisciplinary methodologies, principally geoarchaeological and bioarchaeological, enabling a more detailed characterization of human-environmental relations through notions of palaeoecology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{David and Thomas 2008:31}) \par \emph{Enfasi su must (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=31}{note on p.31})} \par "Settlement patterns in their environmental settings were thus an important focus at the time, along with spatial patterning of environmental variables." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "Together, detailed data on environmental and cultural distributions were targeted, so as to better characterize the economic nature and reasoning behind settlement-subsistence systems and patterns." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "This was much the underlying logic of both the adaptive thinking of the New Archaeology in the United States" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "It is during this period of focus on past humanenvironmental relations that fi eld surveying strategies began to change from site-based to "off-site"" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "(or "non-site" or "siteless") surveys" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "with a greater emphasis on probability sampling" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "because it was quickly realized that what were often effectively continuous (but varied) artifact distributions across the landscape had to be accurately characterized and cross-referenced with environmental variables." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "In the United States" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "ynergistically with the development of the "regional" approach that helped defi ne the New Archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "T" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "his rethinking of surveying methodology took hold both in the United Kingdom and the United States, in many ways world leaders in landscape archaeology at that time, although such developments also took place in many other countries" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "But in the United Kingdom" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "partly through developments in methods aimed at exploring settlement and artifact patterning, there came a realization that archaeologists were" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=32}{David and Thomas 2008:32}) \par "not simply dealing with humans adapting to environmental circumstances, but rather with people interacting among themselves as much as they were interacting with their physical environments" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par "relationship between spatial distributions of material culture and human identities" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par "Hodder and others to the insight that the adoption of specifi c artifact types might represent a deliberate strategy of social inclusion and exclusion, rather than simply refl ecting a pregiven identity." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par "These included symbolic practices that required social and philosophical rather than environmental understandings to decipher. This key period heralded the beginning of contemporary notions of landscape archaeology. This broad shift toward social dimensions of landscapes expands the earlier emphasis on more behavioral modes of interaction." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par "The move toward a more socially oriented landscape archaeology came from many fronts, and it came together as part of a broadly changing culture of understanding. Four major infl uences on archaeological practices were (1) sourcing studies; (2) the rising importance of cultural heritage management and public archaeology; (3) a developing interest in "style;" and (4) Indigenous critiques." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par "In his infl uential paper, "Trade as action at a distance," Colin Renfrew (1975) argued that social change often occurred simultaneously over wide geographical expanses, necessitating a focus not just on individual places but on relationships between places in systems of peer polity interactions." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par \emph{IMPORTANTE (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{note on p.33})} \par "This recognition gave new impetus for a socially oriented economic archaeology, in particular an emphasis on trade." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=33}{David and Thomas 2008:33}) \par "The late 1960s into the 1970s saw major transformations to cultural heritage management, the working face of public archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "Along with a major infl ux in the scale and rate of cultural heritage studies came an increasing need for explicit assessment of the signifi cance of sites and landscapes as cultural resource catchments." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "The need for increased protection of archaeological sites was prefaced by new and explicit criteria for the assessment of" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "heritage places as locations of social signifi cance" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "Hence recognition of the educational, cultural, historical and aesthetic values of archaeological sites and landscapes effectively rendered them signifi cant public places that went beyond their environmental and academic signifi cance" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "These new social dimensions of signifi cance, as expressions of public recognition, meant that the signifi cance of archaeological sites and archaeological landscapes could no longer be reduced to environmental, ecological, or economic agendas" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "In the case of Stonehenge, it is now very diffi cult to imagine the monument in a landscape that is either purely "ecological" in character, or socially uncontested." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "These new directions are well illustrated by the United Nations Educational, Scientifi c and Cultural Organization's (UNESCO) criteria for the inclusion of places in the World Heritage list, which include "archaeological sites that are of outstanding universal value from the historical, aesthetic, ethnological, or anthropological points of view"" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "These criteria were adopted by UNESCO at its 17\textsuperscript{th} session, held in Paris in 1972," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "Another, slightly distinct aspect of cultural resource management that has also fueled the growing concern with social landscapes has been the changing character of "salvage" or "rescue" archaeology in the industrialized nations." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=34}{David and Thomas 2008:34}) \par "Each of these projects has resulted in the recovery of highly important archaeological evidence, but in each case the sheer size of the undertaking has demanded that the investigation must be conceived at the landscape (as opposed to "site") scale." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "Although in some cases it has been possible to address these landscapes in purely environmental terms, for the most part the nature of these projects has required a consideration of social networks that extend beyond residential locations, and the dispersal of social practices across the landscape. Moreover, salvage projects conducted at the multisite level have inevitably often tended to be multiperiod as well, frequently prompting a consideration of landscape development over time." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "A third approach toward the social began to take effect through concerns for the symbolic." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "In "style," the move was toward an understanding of the past that focused more on social relationships within and between communities of people through the way they decorated items of material culture, a move that was also happening in sourcing studies." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "This was not so much an environmentally as a socially informed disciplinary interest, although geographic distance and the presence of geographical barriers limiting the spread of ideas also came into play." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "a new form of landscape archaeology was being fashioned, one that talked of symbolic rather than of environmental confi gurations" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "While archaeologists with interests other than symbolic archaeology were also increasingly involved in ethnoarchaeological research" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=35}{David and Thomas 2008:35}) \par "new concerns with information exchange via symbolic behavior began to refashion landscape archaeology as social archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "A new, largely ethnographically informed focus on the social geography of stylistic behavior among interacting communities of people effectively bridged the gap between an environmental archaeology concerned with artifact and site distributions in physical landscapes and a social and symbolic archaeology interested in the geographical spread of stylistic conventions among archaeological objects" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "But a fourth and most signifi cant infl uence also made its very considerable mark: the realization that environmental notions of landscape archaeology did not by themselves accurately refl ect Indigenous peoples' own notions of their landscapes or the reasons why they lived in certain ways." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "These changes were to some extent connected with a retreat from the more extreme positions of processual archaeology, and its demand for universal laws of human behavior, valid in all temporal and spatial contexts." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "Thus, at the 1982 Australian Archaeological Association (AAA) annual conference, the Indigenous representative Ros Langford (1983) impressed on the audience how the local Aboriginal community had had enough of archaeological characterizations of Indigenous lands and Indigenous history (and through this, the Indigenous present) as an archaeological playground. "Our heritage, your playground" became a rallying point from which to make archaeologists aware of the inadequacy of then-predominant archaeological practices and" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "to change the discipline toward a more socially aware enterprise." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "Together, these four sets of disciplinary developments\textemdash increasing concern with social landscapes as informed by sourcing studies, cultural heritage management, symbolic archaeology, and Indigenous constructions of place\textemdash{} signaled an increasingly anthropological archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "Landscape as country concerns people's relationships with places, a landscape richly inscribed with history, agency, territorial rights, ancestral laws, and behavioral protocols." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "As a result of these critiques, the landscape increasingly began to be seen as engaged socially and culturally as much as it is engaged environmentally, and it is this engagement that defi nes the lie of the land, what a landscape looks like" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "To understand a landscape one has to outline its" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=36}{David and Thomas 2008:36}) \par "means of engagement, the way it is understood, codifi ed, and lived in social practice; and each of these, along with the landscape itself, have history." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=37}{David and Thomas 2008:37}) \par "Such an approach allows for an archaeology not only of monuments but also of so-called natural places (e.g., Bradley 2000), because they, too, are culturally inscribed in social consciousness and therefore possess archaeological signatures defi ned by social attitude." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=37}{David and Thomas 2008:37}) \par "This move toward a more socially informed, and in this a more ethically responsible, landscape archaeology recognizes that the world has many voices. But this recognition has come at a price: some would say that archaeology's innocence has come of age, but others would say that its guilt has been found out, highlighting the discipline's inherently ethical entanglements." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=37}{David and Thomas 2008:37}) \par "In this context, landscape archaeology today is much different from what it was in the 1970s and 1980s." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=37}{David and Thomas 2008:37}) \par "By the fi rst decade of the 21\textsuperscript{st} century, many archaeologists around the world have turned their attention to spiritual dimensions of Indigenous landscapes:" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=37}{David and Thomas 2008:37}) \par "What we now have today is an archaeology of landscapes that is as much about the ontological and cosmological dimensions of places as it is about their physical characteristics. Landscape archaeology has come to refer to the places that are meaningful to people, and in so doing, to the archaeology of that meaningfulness." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=39}{David and Thomas 2008:39}) \par "Th" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=39}{David and Thomas 2008:39}) \par "is, then, is the crux of landscape archaeology: it concerns not only the physical environment onto which people live out their lives but also the meaningful location in which lives are lived" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=39}{David and Thomas 2008:39}) \par "A landscape archaeology is an archaeology of place, not just as defi ned in a set of physical nodes in space (cf. Binford 1982) but in all its lived dimensions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=39}{David and Thomas 2008:39}) \par "This is probably well illustrated by David Clarke's (1968) Analytical Archaeology, a work that is often compared to Americanstyle New Archaeology but that in fact focused more on the logic and methodology of archaeological research as a means of exploring past cultural patterning rather than as a means of elucidating universal laws of cultural process." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=40}{David and Thomas 2008:40}) \par "Within each cultural landscape, people's engagements with place over time have created a material record that provides potential insights for landscape archaeologists. By examining and interpreting that record holistically, researchers can consider its relationship to contemporary cultural landscapes and, in doing so, strengthen the potential for valid statements about past human behavior.10 As Clarke observed, archaeology is the "time dimension" of anthropology and ethnology (1968: 13),11 and when disciplines share a model that deals systematically with each aspect of culture, acknowledging that all these" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=56}{David and Thomas 2008:56}) \par "are mplicated in a dynamic articulation between social and material worlds, a vision emerges of cultural landscapes transforming over time, providing a useful foundation\textemdash an analytic basis of discussion\textemdash through which human-environmental relationships can be understood both in the past and in the present." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=56}{David and Thomas 2008:56}) \par "STRATIGRAPHY, DEPOSITIONAL ENVIRONMENTS, AND PALAEOLANDSCAPE RECONSTRUCTION IN LANDSCAPE ARCHAEOLOGY Nicola Stern" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "This chapter explores how the stratigraphic and sedimentary context of archaeological debris affects the practice of landscape archaeology." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "Only a fraction of the archaeological record consists of material remains that accumulated on (or close to) the surface of the modern landscape." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "Material remains from the remote past are preserved only because they were covered over by sediments, and those sediments usually represent fragments of ancient landscapes that bear little or no relationship to the topographic features or habitats that can be observed in an area today. For this reason, documenting and interpreting the geological context of material remains are fundamental to the practice of landscape archaeology, whatever interpretive approaches are employed to explicate the distribution, density, and characteristics of those remains." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "Over the past three decades, archaeologists have been coming to grips with the interpretative consequences of recognizing that the palaeolandscapes they study are a complex interplay between the physical features of a landscape and people's perceptions of them." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "Not so widely acknowledged are the interpretative consequences of recognizing that the distribution of activity traces results from a complex interplay between the processes of net sediment accumulation and the activities that generated durable material remains" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "Material remains and their encasing sediments accumulated through the operation of different processes, and they did not necessarily accumulate at the same rate or over the same time intervals." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=366}{David and Thomas 2008:366}) \par "For this reason, understanding the way in which archaeological debris and sediments accumulated and the way in which palaeolandscape features are reconstructed is fundamental to the practice of landscape archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=367}{David and Thomas 2008:367}) \par "Not surprisingly, archaeological debris accumulated in different ways and at different rates in different parts of this palaeolandscape (Stern 2004)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=378}{David and Thomas 2008:378}) \par "The stratigraphic and depositional context of a related set of archaeological occurrences establishes the landscape settings in which traces of past activities accumulated. However, the geological context of archaeological materials is not simply a neutral backdrop for investigating the context and characteristics of those activity traces. The way in which, and the time span over which, strata and activity traces accumulated structures the scale and resolution of the palaeolandscape sample." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=378}{David and Thomas 2008:378}) \par "Establishing the time span represented by the sediments making up the palaeolandscape is fundamental to any attempt to study the activity traces accumulated on that landscape. In particular, it provides the basis for identifying the categories of behavioral information that can be generated from the archaeological debris preserved in the palaeolandscape under investigation. This, in turn, helps to identify the analytical and interpretative frameworks considered most appropriate to the empirical structure of the record under investigation." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=378}{David and Thomas 2008:378}) \par "The modern archaeological regional study of landscapes is generally agreed to have started with Willey's (1953) South American settlement pattern surveys." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=552}{David and Thomas 2008:552}) \par "Distributional ("non-site," "siteless," "off-site") approaches, in which past human behavior is conceived as having occurred across entire landscapes, view the surface archaeological record as more or less continuous but variable in organization and density." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "These studies, which focus on the discovery and the recording of individual artifacts, started to be undertaken in the late 1960s" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "but site-based surveys are still common." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "Many studies either combine off-site with sitebased approaches (Alcock and Cherry 2004b: 3) or defi ne "sites" in the laboratory after conducting an off-site survey, for modeling purposes or to satisfy the documentation requirements of government cultural heritage authorities" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "Off-site landscape archaeological studies rapidly expanded from their initial focus on stone artifact distributions to a broader range of elements, including pottery" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "Once a research question is developed, a suitable landscape must be selected, except in CHM contexts, where it is often the case that meaningful research questions have to be devised to fi t a landscape threatened by development." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "Research problems often require a landscape to be representative of a larger area, so the distributional patterns of the surface record and associated human behavioral interpretations can be widely extrapolated." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "A research problem may sometimes only be able to be addressed in a study area containing unique characteristics, so that the research results can inform on a process of great general interest and import-ance." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=553}{David and Thomas 2008:553}) \par "There is a current trend toward the study of smaller and smaller landscapes in more and more detail (Terrenato 2004: 47); this is both a logical and desirable outgrowth from the much more spatially extensive surveys of past decades in many parts of the world, providing complementary datasets suitable for differing 