g that this is not the case" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "These studies support long-held intuitive beliefs by some archaeologists that the relationship between vegetation and surface visibility is complex and nonlinear." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "although mean tract densities of artifacts do increase with ground visibility, there is no linear correlation between individual tract artifact densities and tract visibility" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "and, further, that ground visibility has little predictive effect on site discovery" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "A possible explanation forwarded for this patterning is that the recording of vegetation cover on a ploughed surface is actually a proxy measure for surface weathering" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "Following plowing, both sown crops and/or weeds gradually establish themselves, while at the same time the plowed surface weathers, settles, and defl ates. One of the consequences of this weathering process is that, in addition to being cleaned by rain and irrigation water, artifacts previously lying at least partially within the surface gradually come to rest on the surface . . . Although weeds and crops may grow up through this surface, partially obscuring it in the process, weathering of the surface soils actually acts to make the archaeological component of these soils more visible. (Thompson 2004: 77)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "There may also be "archaeologist effects" that partially counteract the masking of surfaces by vegetation, including these: (1) archaeologists try harder to fi nd artifacts or sites when vegetation reaches a certain density threshold\textemdash this may take the form of walking just a little more slowly across an overgrown tract than across a freshly ploughed one, resulting in more items being found than expected;" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "when vegetation cover is dense, but patchy, the archaeologist's gaze is directed away from the vegetation and onto any expanses of bare ground, so these are scrutinized with greater intensity than they would be under more open conditions, again resulting in unexpectedly high artifact, or more particularly, site discovery rates;" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "archaeologists will discover large, dense scatters almost regardless of surface vegetation cover\textemdash skilled eyes will not miss such scatters if virtually any ground surface is visible." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "The other side of landscape formation is, of course, human land-use history, particularly largescale ground disturbance activities." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=554}{David and Thomas 2008:554}) \par "In some cases, landscape-wide cultural formation processes are directly relevant to the subject of interest, rather than simply something to be measured as a negative effect on the record." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "For example, when research involves study of the development of agriculture, then evidence of landclearing and cultivation, terracing, construction of water control systems, and the like are phenomena that the survey will probably be designed to record." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "To another archaeologist interested only in nonagricultural systems, these activities may be of interest mainly in regard to their effects on transforming the targeted record." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "After decades of study and experimentation, archaeologists have some understanding of the effects of ploughing" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "Essentially, what has been learned is that: (1) some horizontal dispersion of clusters of items does occur after initial ploughing, so that they are found archaeologically as somewhat larger, less dense clusters or scatters on a ploughed surface" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "(2) around 5\% of the artifacts in the ploughzone will be exposed on the surface after a ploughing event" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "arger items come to the surface disproportionately frequently" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "It has been suggested that cultivated surfaces should be surveyed more than once, each time following a ploughing episode, to obtain a representative sample of the contents of the ploughzone" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "although this may not always be practical, particularly in CHM situations" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "Various factors obscure, expose, or remove aspects of the surface archaeological record" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "The effects of surface vegetation" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "smallscale sedimentation" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "surface sediment type" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "ploughing" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "or amateur artifact collecting" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "on a survey sample should be considered by archaeologists, but one approach, particularly in CHM applications, involves the" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "calculation of "effective survey" and related correction formulae" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "This is a highly fraught road to take in that the effects of vegetation or sedimentation on the visibility of the surface archaeological record are highly landscape-specifi c, locally variable (Fanning and Holdaway 2004), and changeable over short durations (Burger et al. 2004: 418)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "The application of simple cookbook formulas risks introducing more distortion and uncertainty than they are likely to "correct" for, especially if formation issues have not been adequately considered analytically for the landscape under study" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "Once the characteristics of the selected landscape are understood, choosing the other elements of the survey strategy largely involves decisions based on sampling considerations" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "Survey intensity is "the degree of detail with which the ground surface of a given survey unit is inspected"" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{David and Thomas 2008:555}) \par "and is commonly measured by the spacing between individual surveyors walking parallel paths (commonly referred to as "transects")" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8PRTF3QS?page=555}{D