@PhdThesis{Lawrence2012,
  author    = {Lawrence, Dan},
  title     = {Early {{Urbanism}} in the {{Northern Fertile Crescent}}: {{A Comparison}} of {{Regional Settlement Trajectories}} and {{Millennial Landscape Change}}},
  year      = {2012},
  address   = {{Durham}},
  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (21/2/2022, 15:09:26)} \par "whilst the distribution of sites of different sizes and morphologies may be related to settlement hierarchies and, by inference, degrees of social complexity (" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "Incorporating off-site features allows for the reconstruction of past land-use and agricultural practices (" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "and the identification of relationships between settlement patterns, natural features such as topography and water bodies, and man-made systems such as canals and routes" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "Analysis of these interactions is predicated on our ability to reconstruct past landscapes from the material traces visible in the present. A second aim of this study is therefore to investigate landscape transformation processes, the ways in which successive occupations of the same area result in the attenuation of the archaeological record. The methods by which such a study may be accomplished are discussed in Chapter 2." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "impossible to examine the lay-out of settlement or land-use practices as they would have appeared even at the level of a lifetime" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "Focusing on long term and large scale trends effectively aggregates the lives of individuals into a series of processes in a manner which may appear both generalising and reductive" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "One answer focuses on the emergent properties of landscapes as the products of repeated collective human actions over time" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "Whilst the specific motivations and concerns of the people involved in the production of a particular set of material traces may be unknown (and perhaps unknowable), the fact that the process itself continued at a scale beyond that of the individual demonstrates the presence of a larger set of social 'rules'." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "The relationship between societal or structural rules and the individuals who enact them has been the subject of considerable debate in the social sciences, and especially in the disciplines of sociology and anthropology (see, for example, Giddens 1984; Bourdieu 1990) where the individuals in question are available to answer questions personally." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=31}{Lawrence 2012:31}) \par "rules which govern collective behaviour over the agency of the individual." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "This is not to say that the agency of certain powerful individuals cannot have a profound impact on the landscape." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "Analysis of trends at a regional level requires a theoretical basis capable of articulating and understanding large scale variation." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "World Systems Theory (WST)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "Kohl 1979; Algaze 1989; 2005 [1993])." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "Core areas exert a degree of political and economic control over peripheries through the monopolisation of technology and other means of producing finished goods, resulting in highly asymmetric trade and exchange relationships" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "Peripheries provide raw materials to core areas which are then transformed into high-value products to be consumed in the core and also exported back to the periphery" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "In recent years the application of WST to archaeological data has been criticised on a number of levels. Initially, these critiques centred on the insistence of the primacy of the core area as a causal factor in the trajectory of the entire system, and the assumption of complete core dominance over every aspect of peripheral existence. Later formulations of the theory have sought to downplay this primacy (Hall and Chase-Dunn 1993), but the structuring role" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "Perhaps the most fully realised articulation of WST in the Near East is that presented for the Uruk period th by Algaze (1989; 2005 [1993]). Algaze considers the competing polities which emerged during the 4 millennium in Southern Mesopotamia to represent a core, controlling an informal economic, and in some areas actively colonial, empire stretching into Northern Mesopotamia along the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, and into Turkey and Susiana in Iran. Like the larger theory on which it is based, this model has been subject to significant critique on both theoretical and empirical grounds. Evidence from sites such as Hacinebi and Arslantepe in Turkey and Brak and Hamoukar in the Khabur basin in Syria has demonstrated that the Late Chalcolithic societies in Algaze's periphery zone were highly complex prior to the Uruk period. Further, the interaction between potential Southern Mesopotamian settlers and local populations was not one of direct domination in either the political or economic spheres" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=32}{Lawrence 2012:32}) \par "of the overall interaction between core and periphery is still given greater theoretical weight than local developments in either zone." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "Such a focus on regional and interregional scale interaction does not sufficiently address the importance of local social and environmental factors and the competing agencies of various groups and individuals within the societies involved in the world system (B" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "the concepts still hold some value as metaphors for relationships at a regional scale, particularly when combined with the sort of empirical data available in the FCP." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "Through close analysis of survey and other archaeological data it is clearly possible to differentiate between areas in relation to settlement density, settlement hierarchy and, to some degree, political organisation, as well as in the stability of settlement through time." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "Analysis at a super-community level requires some way of articulating these differences. However, as Stein has rightly pointed out, '(a)s soon as we start to call some regions "core areas" and others "peripheries," we have already structured the discourse...between the two areas into an inherently unequal relationship" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "'sub-optimal regions' (Philip and Bradbury 2010; Bradbury 2011) and 'marginal environments' (Geyer and Calvet 2001; Geyer et al. 2007)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "they do represent a useful step forward." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "heir main advantage is that they allow for an understanding of environmental constraints whilst still incorporating the contingent and dynamic nature of human-landscape interaction." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "landscapes. Wossink, for example, sees the steppe zone as one suitable for occupation 'only under specific socio-cultural and economic conditions' and stresses that such conditions are subject to change through time" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "Importantly, the possibility for more than one core area to exist within a larger region has also been recognised, and in fact stressed as an important generative factor in early state formation (Wright 2005)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "Given the purview of this study, it is necessary to be able to recognise both cores and margins through survey data. In this case, core zones may be defined as those areas which demonstrate high agricultural potential, long term" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=33}{Lawrence 2012:33}) \par "stability, high settlement densities and complex site hierarchies and settlement patterns relative to other occupied areas" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=34}{Lawrence 2012:34}) \par "Sub-optimal or marginal zones are those which experience significant fluctuations in settlement density and structure through time. We might also add a third category of landscape, those which are never densely settled and in which humans have little impact" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=34}{Lawrence 2012:34}) \par "regional analysis requires the archaeologist" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=34}{Lawrence 2012:34}) \par "o define core and sub-optimal areas in the landscape through time (2) to identify the socio-cultural and economic conditions which explain the fluctuations in the margins and (3) to relate these to the trajectories of settlement in the core zones and the conditions which prevailed there" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=34}{Lawrence 2012:34}) \par "For the dry farming part of the Fertile Crescent investigated in this study, a key environmental constraint affecting the agricultural productivity of a landscape is rainfall, both in terms of absolute amounts and in annual fluctuations (Cocks et al. 1988; Wilkinson 1997; 2000c)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=34}{Lawrence 2012:34}) \par "Based on this rainfall distribution and studies of modern agricultural practices, Wachholtz (1996) has defined a 'zone of permanence' and a 'zone of transition' for the landscapes of northern Syria, and particularly the area to the south east of Aleppo" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=34}{Lawrence 2012:34}) \par "he zone of transition receives between 250 and 180mm of rainfall allowing for limited cultivation of barley, with sheep and goat herding predominant. Below the 180mm limit dry farming is not possible and occupation is restricted to semi-nomadic Bedu groups" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "Using Wachholtz's model, Wilkinson has defined a 'zone of uncertainty' for agricultural production equivalent to the 'zone of transition' in modern times, stretching from the southern Jazira to the Middle Euphrates and Ebla (2000c; 27; fig." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "potentially productive landscape given the right social, political and economic conditions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "Using 7 modern day rainfall as a guide , it is possible to extend this zone into central and southern Syria, and even the southern Levant. The degree to which this may reflect rainfall levels in the past is a matter of some debate (see above). In the face of these uncertainties it is best to understand the zone of uncertainty as a heuristic interpretive device rather than a cast iron definition of settlement divisions or subsistence practices" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "It should be noted from the outset that I am not attempting a full scale reanalysis of any of the individual surveys which make up the FCP; the aim is rather to organise and integrate them in such a way as to allow larger trends to emerge." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "However, research agendas, methods and technological changes over the 40 year period in which the surveys were undertaken have resulted in significant differences in the data generated" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "Chapter 3 for" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "In order to investigate and mitigate the effects of these changes, and to retain the level of empirical rigour I have argued is vital for broad scale regional comparisons, it has been necessary to discuss the survey results in some detail" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "This limited reanalysis builds upon the original survey reports but also updates them in light of both later scholarship and interpretations possible through remote sensing data which may not have been available or used in the original survey." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "larger continuous areas than was possible in the original surveys" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "Where possible, chronological uncertainties have also been resolved through the incorporation of results from later sequences" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "For reasons of space, the need to update the surveys has also led to a focus on the data itself as opposed to interpretations relating to broader social and political processes," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "The rainfall isohyet demarcations used in this study are taken from Wirth (1971) and are derived from long term averages collected at a variety of weather stations over several years" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=35}{Lawrence 2012:35}) \par "discussion of data across a region and the desire to produce interpretations at a broad scale is worth noting, particularly given the constrained nature of most forms of mainstream academic publication currently available." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "To develop methods for the integration of datasets derived from multiple landscape surveys, satellite imagery analysis and cartographic data into a single interpretive framewo" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "To further compare the subsequent settlement histories across the same region and assess the impact of later occupation on the archaeological record To assess whether trends in settlement and landscape use are visible at a regional level " (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "Chapter 2 reviews" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "Chapter 3 provides" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "Chapter 4 addresses" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "and sets out a method through which these diverse datasets can be combined." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "each case, detailed analysis of settlement and land-use is th th rd provided for the late 5 , 4 and 3 millennia, along with more general trends observable in the long term" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=36}{Lawrence 2012:36}) \par "This geographical division has been retained in the first stages of analysis as a way of negotiating the enormous amount of data involved in this study. Along with a relatively high degree of