8}) \par "the burial of smaller settlement mounds entirely (Adams 1981). In order to get around this problem, archaeologists must be able to predict the types of settlements and features which may have been lost" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=38}{Lawrence 2012:38}) \par "therefore necessary to investigate the processes behind deposition itself." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=38}{Lawrence 2012:38}) \par "Two factors bring about changes in the amount of deposition over time;" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=38}{Lawrence 2012:38}) \par "amount of rainfall combined with resulting vegetation shifts," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=38}{Lawrence 2012:38}) \par "anthropogenic deforestation" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=38}{Lawrence 2012:38}) \par "climate," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=38}{Lawrence 2012:38}) \par "Wagstaff relates the formation of the Younger Fill to economic decline in the Late Roman period, suggesting that a combination of high taxation and labour shortages resulted in the degradation of terracing systems and therefore the release of sediment by erosion into river systems" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "Of particular interest in the case of Bronze Age Syria and the Levant is the widespread deforestation which may have taken place at that time, evidenced in palynological analysis and lake cores" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "The Bronze Age, where most of the settlement is confined to river and wadi valleys (in the North) as well as canal systems (in the South), is particularly affected" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "widely" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "accepted that deforestation and the general clearing of land for agriculture has had a significant impact on the landscape." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "both local and regional levels." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "Geomorphological processes can change the material existence of sites, such as the deep gullies and alluvial fans found at larger tells like Brak in the Syrian Jazira, as well as masking or entirely obscuring smaller sites and features across vast regions such as the alluvial plains of southern Iraq" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "significant alluvial and colluvial deposits will be confined to river valleys." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=39}{Lawrence 2012:39}) \par "In order to investigate landscapes it is vital to build a theoretical framework from which to deal with both natural and cultural processes" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "One such framework, first articulated by Taylor (Taylor 1972) and developed by Williamson (1987; 1998) and Wilkinson (2003; 41-43), involves delineating certain landscapes as zones of destruction and zones of survival" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "ny human trace left on the landscape will remain there until it is destroyed, over-run or incorporated into a later landscape." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "mall and often upland areas where later peoples never lived, and only rarely cultivated" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "greater part of the country where later people have largely or partly destroyed the evidence" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "Williamson emphasises the relationship between land used for the purposes of arable and land used for pasture" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "Further, pristine prehistoric landscapes do survive in upland areas where arable-based agriculture and settlement has generally been sparse" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "The theoretical framework in which the landscape is divided into zones of destruction and preservation has been adapted and applied to the Near East, particularly by Wilkinson (2003). Wilkinson incorporates Schiffer's (1987) conception of cand n-transformations, meaning cultural and natural respectively, into the Taylor/Williamson model, and also uses the idea of 'signature landscapes'" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=40}{Lawrence 2012:40}) \par "He divides the Near East into five zones, each of which allows for a different degree or different kind of landscape preservation." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=41}{Lawrence 2012:41}) \par "The mountain and desert regions, rarely settled and often abruptly abandoned, provide the most complete signature landscapes," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=41}{Lawrence 2012:41}) \par "whilst the intermediate zone, of which the Jazira is a prime example, contain a varied settlement pattern in which social, political and climatic factors may affect the extension of settlement and therefore the preservation of relic landscapes." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=41}{Lawrence 2012:41}) \par "The zone of attrition encompasses land that has been continuously or nearcontinuously occupied" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=41}{Lawrence 2012:41}) \par "This is particularly significant for river valleys." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/8FTH5UFM?page=41}{Lawrence 2012:41}) \par "We might add to the definition zones in which a significant replanning of the landscape has taken place, such as that brought about by centuriation during the Roman 