  editor    = {Cherry, John and Alcock, Susan},
  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (22/2/2022, 08:27:30)} \par "When compared with Mediterranean surveys, most surveys conducted in the Near East seem extensive, inaccurate and idiosyncratic. Interestingly, however, some of the problems raised by these apparently coarse-grained surveys raise issues of wider relevance, especially to the development of early states and empires." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=1}{Wilkinson et al 2004:198}) \par "At face value, this shift in settlement structure appears to represent a change from one very basic form of political organization - the 'city-state' or chiefdom (itself a contentious issue!) - toward a settlement pattern that developed in association with large territorial empires." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=1}{Wilkinson et al 2004:198}) \par "In order to tackle this problem, it is necessary to compare evidence from archaeological surveys conducted over a large geographical area, as well as to make certain that there is some degree of comparability of evidence. These factors are essential because over the last few years it has become clear that the rather coarse techniques of traditional surveys in the Near East are, in fact, quite successful at recording the settlement of certain periods. Nevertheless they prove to be hopelessly inadequate for other periods." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=1}{Wilkinson et al 2004:198}) \par "Interestingly, this shows that surveys in, for example, the plains of upper Mesopotamia (including more recent surveys with off-site control) have a stubborn tendency to remain in a fairly 'extensive' category compared with Mediterranean surveys. When the number of sites is plotted according to the size of the survey area, Near Eastern surveys recover between 1 site per 10 sq. km and 1 site per sq. km (Figure 14.1). In other words, they show a higher rate of recovery than 'earlier Greek surveys' (i.e. those before the 1970s), but are well below those conducted between, say, 1970 and the early 1980s, and certainly much less than the surveys of the 1990s. Even when occupation periods (i.e. on multi-period sites) are plotted per survey area, the number of occupations per sq. km still does not attain that of most intensive Mediterranean surveys (Figure 14.1: 4a, 5a and 8a). This suggests immediately that Near Eastern surveys continue to be somewhat antiquated in terms of techniques of site recognition and recovery." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=1}{Wilkinson et al 2004:198}) \par "Alternatively, however, these statistics may represent a real difference between the pattern of settlement in the Near East and the Mediterranean, and surveys in the Upper Mesopotamian plains could imply that site densities were, in fact, significantly lower than in the Mediterranean. That this is the case is suggested by some surveys conducted in arid areas along the desert margins. These yield higher 'site' densities than occur in sub-humid regions. This unexpected disparity can be explained in the following ways:" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=1}{Wilkinson et al 2004:198}) \par "Schiffer 1987" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=2}{Wilkinson et al 2004:199}) \par "post-Bronze Age dispersed settlement appears as low, often straggling, mounds of farmsteads and villages. Towns and cities of course occur in the post-Bronze Age periods, but these are usually extensive mounds that are more widely distributed. These include, for example, regional Neo-Assyrian centers such" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=3}{Wilkinson et al 2004:200}) \par "In the sub-humid plains of western Syria and southern Turkey, although the same pattern is evident, it is less clear and instead there is a tendency for Iron Age settlements to exhibit a mixed tell-based (nucleated) and dispersed pattern of settlement" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "All three surveys used a similar methodology. A fullcoverage approach was employed, with each unit of the survey universe being examined with an equal intensity" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "survey universe being examined with an equal intensity. Sites were initially identified via remote sensing: aerial photography, and detailed topographic maps (NJS), SPOT imagery (TBS), and CORONA satellite photography (THS; see Ur 2003); these sites were then visited by vehicle and collected by dividing up the surface into topographically discrete units from which a large sample of diagnostic sherds was collected. The No" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "The North Jazira and Hamoukar surveys both included a program of off-site survey, which entailed walking systematic transects between sites or according to a grid-pattern of sample points. By collecting field-scatters and pinpointing (remarkably rare) minor artifact-scatters, this program allowed us roughly to compare these north Mesopotamian surveys with the more intensive surveys conducted around the Mediterranean" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "site was regarded as a locus of concentrated human activity, assumed to entail residence for all or part of a year" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "The definition of a 'site' is of particular relevance to this comparison. In the three surveys discussed here, a site was regarded as a locus of concentrated human activity, assumed to entail residence for all or part of a year. This definition distinguishes traditional 'sites' from fieldscatters, which also represent human activity but at a much" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "distinguishes traditional 'sites' from fieldscatters, which also represent human activity but at a much" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "lower intensity" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "wer intensity. A combination of three criteria was used to identify and delimit sites archaeologically: sherd den" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "combination of three criteria was used to identify and delimit sites archaeologically" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "density, topography, and soils" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "ls. On-site sherd density tended to be at least 150-200 sherds per 100 sq. m under most site surface conditions; field scatter density averaged between 10-60 sherds per 100 sq. m on fallow fields, although proximity to third-millennium sites and local field conditions affected these averages. Field-scatters are nearly invisible in plowed fields, and are frequently in the range of 70-100 sherds per 100 sq. m within 1500 m of urban third-millennium sites. On the Upper Mesopotamian plains, mudbrick was the prima" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "On the Upper Mesopotamian plains, mudbrick was the primary building material, and thus ancient sites tend to be mounded. On the one hand, concentrated on-site human activity inhibited soil formation, whereas the contribution of human and animal wasteproducts and middens resulted in a lighter and finer-grained anthropogenic soil, which stands out from the darker and red-hued calcareous soils (calcic xerosols) of the plains." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=4}{Wilkinson et al 2004:201}) \par "The NJS area supported 78 Iron Age villages in the range of 1-5 ha, which were evenly spaced across the plain" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=5}{Wilkinson et al 2004:202}) \par "scatter of some 35 sites of Iron Age date was established in valley floors, on low upland watersheds and even on the otherwise unoccupied basalt plateau" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=5}{Wilkinson et al 2004:202}) \par "Of these, most were single-period 'new foundations', although some also yielded pottery of the LBA and even Mittanian periods" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=5}{Wilkinson et al 2004:202}) \par "In the THS area" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=5}{Wilkinson et al 2004:202}) \par "the five largest EBA tells had Iron Age 'lower town' settlements; the other 16 Iron Age sites were either new foundations on the plain or were reoccupations of low mounds which had been abandoned since the fourth millennium or earlier" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=6}{Wilkinson et al 2004:203}) \par "In the NJS area, Iron Age ceramics were found in field-scatters, but only half as frequently as EBA types" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=6}{Wilkinson et al 2004:203}) \par "slopes of EBA tells are they associated with denser fieldscatters In the THS area, only where Iron Age settlements are found on the" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=6}{Wilkinson et al 2004:203}) \par "Age sites associated with hollow-ways; only those Iron Age settlements on older EBA sites have associated hollow-ways, but in many cases these can be directly associated with features of the EBA site such as walls and gates, rather than with any features dating to the Iron Age" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=7}{Wilkinson et al 2004:204}) \par "Most Middle Eastern surveys cannot be compared with Mediterranean surveys for methodological reasons:" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "they tend to rely heavily on non-systematic vehicular reconnaissance supplemented by remote-sensing sources, as opposed to the systematic field-walking transect methods favored in the Mediterranean" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "few have included a program of systematic 'off-site' transect-walking at set intervals. However, the NJS and the THS included systematic 'off-site' landscape observation as part of the study of field-scatters." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "the NJS, radial transects were walked around and between the major EBA sites and many kilometers of sections of a 500 m irrigation canal grid were systematically investigated for traces of buried sites" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "the THS, a threeperson team made 100 sq. m field-scatter unit collections in a 200 m UTM-based grid; this involved walking transects at 200 m intervals" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Admittedly, this resolution is coarse when compared to Mediterranean surveys, but the Jaziran sample methods do serve as a rough check on the remote-sensing sources. In the fall of 2000, when the THS transects were made, most fields were fallow or harvested and grazed. Visibility was very high;" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "After walking over some 56,000 m of transects and collecting almost 500 units, the THS found no sites that had not already been recognized on CORONA photographs" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "landscape of destruction" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Taylor-Williamson model, these are areas where progressive loss of features should be at its maximum" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "where we should expect to find 'ghosts' of sites remaining" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Yet when field-walking has been included in the survey methods (NJS and THS), very few additional sites have been recovered." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "the choice of mudbrick as the primary building materials and the floodplain geomorphology in these regions have acted to make sites much more visible than in the Mediterranean area." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Scarcity of timber resources in these and other areas of the Middle East has meant that mudbrick has been the most common building material almost since the beginnings of sedentary settlement. Since it is more efficient to make new mudbricks than to reuse old ones, there has been little, if any, deconstruction or robbing of abandoned settlements for building materials. Mudbrick sites pose few difficulties for agriculture: whereas a stone settlement" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "a mudbrick site can be plowed over directly." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "This process results in the slight dispersal of archaeological materials across the landscape, but even on late Neolithic sites, mounding is still preserved after millennia of subsequent agriculture and a half-century of mechanized plowing. In other words, although long-term taphonomic processes have resulted in the attrition of many (but not all) landscape features, a large number of the original settlements appear to remain." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "the Jazira of upper Mesopotamia, if high-resolution remote-sensing sources are combined with intensive field-survey, a reasonable approximation of full recovery is theoretically possible." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Moreover, a degree of site recovery comparable to that of the intensive Mediterranean surveys is possible using much less intensive methods. This statement applies only to the plains of northern Syria and northern Iraq; few highland areas of Northern Mesopotamia have been subjected to intensive survey." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "These near-ideal survey conditions may not pertain for much longer" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Moreover, probably the greatest cause of loss of archaeological sites is where they are obscured below modern villages. Even where pottery can be recognized between the modern houses the individual sherds are frequently abraded down to small sizes so that they are difficult to place typologically." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "It is possible that real differences in long-term cultural practices existed between these regions, particularly a 'settlement inertia' on the plains of North Mesopotamia, whereby a positive feedback-loop caused people both to remain within their communities and to return to previously settled places" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=8}{Wilkinson et al 2004:205}) \par "Courtois 1973)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=9}{Wilkinson et al 2004:206}) \par "in northern Mesopotamia, in the first millennium" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=9}{Wilkinson et al 2004:206}) \par "BC the northern Levant witnessed a pronounced dispersal" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=10}{Wilkinson et al 2004:207}) \par "of settlement away from nucleated tell sites, and towards much smaller sites that are spread across the plains and into surrounding highlands." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=10}{Wilkinson et al 2004:207}) \par "Excavations at Chatal H\"oy\"uk found that the large Iron Age city" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=10}{Wilkinson et al 2004:207}) \par "Tell Judaidah" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=10}{Wilkinson et al 2004:207}) \par "Haines 1971)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=10}{Wilkinson et al 2004:207}) \par "Overall, in northern Iraq, northern Syria and southern Turkey traditional surveys appear to have been reasonably effective at recognizing the basic pattern of Bronze Age settlement, but they have proved to be woefully inadequate for accurately recovering the pattern of settlement of the Iron Age" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "In many areas, settlement dispersal commenced during the second half of the second millennium BC, and by the Iron Age there had been a pronounced extension of settlement into the steppe or uplands. This dispersal has been recorded in much of the Jazira (" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "the Jabbul plain" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "and the Levant" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "Furthermore, during the Hellenistic, Roman and Late Antique periods the development of a rural landscape dominated by a dispersed pattern of rural settlement became even more pronounced in the southern Levant, as well as the Euphrates region of southern Turkey and parts of northern Syria" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "Recent surveys undertaken at a greater level of intensity and with more regard for smaller sites, support the above statement, but in the Jazira of Northern Syria and Iraq, this statement is more appropriate for the Iron Age, as well as for the later periods in some parts of the region" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "other places this pattern of dispersed settlement appears to have been built upon foundations that were laid during the Iron Age" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "e.g. northern Iraq: Wilkinson and Tucker 1995)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "The striking change in settlement structure that took place between the mid-third and the first millennium BC appears to represent a major shift from complex 'citystate'-type settlement systems during the Bronze Age toward the territorial empires of the first millennium BC" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "Such a transformation, which was probably associated with the collapse of the Late Bronze Age political economy, may be linked to wide-ranging changes in land-tenure, as well as to shifts in the exercising of power and population redistributions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "it is crucial for settlement surveys to be conducted, in both lowlands and nearby uplands, to a rigorous and standardized methodology. Moreover, it is also important to take into account differences in landscape taphonomy (both physical and cultural transformations), as well as local mechanisms of site development that reinforce earlier patterns of settlement." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "In" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "the THS it can be demonstrated in several places that subsequent (post-EBA) settlements took advantage of the borrow-pit potential of disused hollow-way troughs (Ur" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par ")." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "2002b). From a" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "(U" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "2002b). From a social and ideational perspective, tells and mounds probably retained a deeper significance that cannot be recovered archaeologically." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "Additional social factors contribute to nucleation" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=14}{Wilkinson et al 2004:211}) \par "The nature of land-holding may also have militated against settlement dispersal." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=15}{Wilkinson et al 2004:212}) \par "The new lands which experienced such settlement may therefore have been either deliberate re-settlement schemes of land not previously cultivated (as in the case of Neo-Assyrian re-settlement), spontaneous settlement by nomadic groups (such as the Aramaeans" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=15}{Wilkinson et al 2004:212}) \par "or perhaps piecemeal settlement of uplands by individuals who acquired or purchased land outside the traditional land-holding system" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=15}{Wilkinson et al 2004:212}) \par "he tendency toward settlement nucleation and continuity manifests itself archaeologically in the form of multi-period sites." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=15}{Wilkinson et al 2004:212}) \par "when settlements are dispersed and form singleperiod flat sites, their recognition is difficult, but each occupational phase can be more securely dated because of the lack of overlying deposits" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=15}{Wilkinson et al 2004:212}) \par "Although certain settlement landscapes may tentatively be related to the prevailing political economy, the tantalizing relationship between settlement pattern and large-" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=15}{Wilkinson et al 2004:212}) \par "scale administrative structures, such as states or empires, will need considerably more research to determine whether it can be upheld" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "More important, we believe, are factors that lead to changes in settlement structure and morphology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "In areas near the Mediterranean where there is clear evidence for Hellenistic-Byzantine settlement dispersal, surveys are in danger of identifying the dispersed phase of settlement in the uplands, but missing the long-term record of lowland settlement. This is because lowland settlement may have been obscured by deposition, especially by sediments eroded from the surrounding hills during the post-Hellenistic phase of settlement dispersal. The final result of such a survey - very little occupation on the plains and post-Hellenistic settlement on the hills - could therefore show little resemblance to the true picture of long-lived settlement" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Overall, rather than becoming obsessed with the details of site recovery, it is necessary for surveyors to also become more sensitive to settlement structure, landscape taphonomy, processes of settlement formation, as well as interactions between settlement and geomorphology. Attention to these factors, together with site recovery and comparability of datacollections, should considerably improve our ability to compare neighboring survey records" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Algaze, G., Breuninger, R. and Knutstad, J. (1994) The TigrisEuphrates Archaeological Reconnaissance Project: final report of the Birecik and Carchemish Dam survey areas. Anatolica 20: 1-96" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Banning, E. B. (1996) Highlands and lowlands: problems and survey frameworks for rural archaeology in the Near East." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "rker, G. W. W. (1996) Regional archaeological projects: trends and traditions in Mediterranean archaeology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Cherry, J. F. (1983)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Courtois, J.-C. (1973) Prospection archa\'eologique dans la moyenne vall\'ee de l'Oronte" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Morandi, D. B. (2000)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Schiffer, M. B. (1987) Formation Processes of the Archaeological Record" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=16}{Wilkinson et al 2004:213}) \par "Schwartz, G. M., Curvers" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=17}{Wilkinson et al 2004:214}) \par "Taylor, C. C. (1972" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=17}{Wilkinson et al 2004:214}) \par "Van Liere, W. J. and Lauffray, J. (1954-55) Nouvelle prospection arch\'eologique dans la Haute Jezireh Syrienne." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=17}{Wilkinson et al 2004:214}) \par "Verstraete, J. and Wilkinson, T.J. (2000) The Amuq Regional Archaeological Survey" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=17}{Wilkinson et al 2004:214}) \par "Wilkinson, T. J. (1993) Linear hollows in the Jazira, Upper Mesopotamia" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/PFW5WB95?page=17}{Wilkinson et al 2004:214}) \par "Wilkinson, T. J. (2000a) Regional approaches to Mesopotamian archaeology