  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (21/2/2022, 12:51:21)} \par "Archaeological survey provides the means of recovering such settlement patterns; therefore, this field of research is fundamental to an understanding of the development of the early state" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=1}{Wilkinson 2000:219}) \par "The golden age of archaeological survey in Mesopotamia and Iran was arguably in the 1960s and 1970s, when many innovative techniques and theoretical approaches were applied to regional analysis of settlement patterns and economic systems." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=1}{Wilkinson 2000:219}) \par "tion (Redman, 1982, p. 375). This" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "At first, surveys in the Near East were conducted simply to find a good site for excavatio" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "his goal persisted throughout much of the 20\textsuperscript{th} century, although as early as the 1930s Robert Braidwood's Amuq survey sought to find data on the relationship between patterns of settlement and human behavior (Braidwood, 1937). Braidwood's approach was echoed by Lloyd (1954) who appreciated the value of Near Eastern surveys for providing data on the extent and interrelation of "cultural provinces," the comparative density of population, the economy and military sites, the directions of ancient roads, and place names" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "More specifically, Jacobsen's initial survey in the Diyala area in 1936 attempted to establish a relationship between irrigation and settlement by plotting the tells of each period on period maps" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "The objectives of Adams' original surveys were ambitious, namely to provide some level of explanation for the precocious early growth of this "oldest, literate civilization in the world" as well as its precipitous decline" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "there is no doubt that these early surveys contributed enormously to our ability to describe the process of urbanization" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "patterns of differential growth and decline were explicitly tackled, an interpretive framework that has continued up to the present day, albeit now using techniques such as those of Dewar (1991) for establishing more fine-grained population trends" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "Kouchoukos, 1998; Pollock, 1999, pp. 52-77" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=2}{Wilkinson 2000:220}) \par "landscape has been the subject of archaeological surveys since Jacobsen's initial Diyala survey of the 1930s, the more phenomenological approach to landscapes practiced in recent years by postprocessual archaeologists has made little impact in the Near East." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "en though Morandi (1996a), for the Neo-Assyrian Khabur Valley, has explored the concept of "landscapes of power," his methodological approach is more tied to those of the locational models of 1960s geography than to those of the postprocessual schools" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "Whatever the goals of survey, interpretation of patterns of settlement and demographic trends are only as good as the quality of survey data retrieval." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "Thus a 1981 review of the field stated that a current concern of survey archaeology in general was a return to basic questions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "This backto-basics approach included increased emp" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "sed emphasis on site recognition, a shift to more intensive strategies, an appreciation of geomorphological factors and relations between surface and subsurface remains, to which I would add cultural taphonomic processes." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "Such objectives that focus on the nuts and bolts of site recognition and artifact recovery would seem mean-spirited in comparison with the earlier goals of identifying the origins of urbanization and human institutions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "Here I follow a backto-basics approach, with an emphasis on the description of patterns of settlement development, land use, and the economic infrastructure in the form of traces of irrigation and communication systems." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "Consequently, the status of surveys in southern Mesopotamia is simply updated based on results from small surveys that can act as a control on earlier, more extensive field operations, as well as recent reassessments of regional settlement and environment" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "especially those derived from remote sensing." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "Specifically, it is the growth of the last-named methodology that has moved the field forward significantly in recent years, through the use of satellite images to map settlement systems within their environment, and their analysis using Geographical Information Systems" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=3}{Wilkinson 2000:221}) \par "With the burgeoning of surveys and excavations in northern Iraq, the Syrian Jazira, and southern Turkey during the last 20 years, especially in response to major salvage projects, there has been a substantial growth of information. Unfortunately, owing to the location of many salvage projects within river valleys, there has also been a consistent bias in survey coverage. Nevertheless, it is now possible to compare the developmental trajectories of the rain-fed zone with those of the irrigated zone further south in order to see if trends in population growth and urbanization were synchronous within these two contrasting areas." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=4}{Wilkinson 2000:222}) \par "the north was primarily dependent on the extensive farming of rain-fed staple crops, primarily wheat, barley, some legumes, and supplementary animal husbandry" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=4}{Wilkinson 2000:222}) \par "Such large areas, as Weiss has argued, compensated for the relatively low crop yields. The archaeological reconstruction of land-use patterns within several ecological zones of the Jazira provide support for this model of large-scale prairietype agriculture, but with an added emphasis on differential levels of land-use intensity dependent upon location. The combined area of Upper and Lower Mesopotamia include much of the catchment of the Tigris-Euphrates basin that is situated in southeastern Turkey, Syria, and Iraq, but stops at the Iraq/Iran border to the east" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=4}{Wilkinson 2000:222}) \par "Further details of site distributions can be found in Hours et al. (1994), the TAVO Atlas (1988), and Atlas of Archaeological Sites in Iraq (1976)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=5}{Wilkinson 2000:223}) \par "Archaeological surveyors in the Near East often cling tenaciously to traditional modes of site survey, in part, because large conspicuous sites on plains form an important part of the record, and by default the smaller sites have sometimes been deemed less important." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=5}{Wilkinson 2000:223}) \par "nt. Because of this focus on tells the adoption of intensive survey and sampling techniques has often been sluggish. Consequently, the recognition of aceramic Neolithic sites (see Table II; Watkins, 1998, p. 4), or settlements of mobile communities has been inhibited. A" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=5}{Wilkinson 2000:223}) \par "An additional problem is that inadequacies in the dating of ceramics result not only in major gaps in the record but also in long ceramic periods (Table II), and therefore sites that are ceramically contemporaneous may not necessarily have been occupied at the same time" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=5}{Wilkinson 2000:223}) \par "4 Carchemish-Biricik survey Algaze et al. (1991), Algaze et al. (1994) (Turkey) 5 Tishrin Copeland and Moore, (1985), McClellan and" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "Porter (1990)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "Sajur Besan{\c }con et al. (1980), Sanlaville (1985)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "7 Tabqa Dam (Syria) Van Loon (1967), Zettler (1997, Fig. 1.3)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "6 Sajur Besan{\c }con et al. (1980), Sanlaville (1985). 7 Tabqa Dam (Syria) Van Loon (1967), Zettler (1997, Fig. 1.3) 8 Jabbul Maxwell-Hyslop et al. (1942/1943)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "9 Mid-Euphrates a Kohlmeyer (1984, 1986)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "0 Mid-Euphrates b Geyer and Monchambert (1987), Monchambert (1983) 11 Mid-Euphrates c Simpson (1983)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "33 Haditha Dam Abdul-Amir (1988)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=6}{Wilkinson 2000:224}) \par "The existence of a fine-grained local ceramic typology, therefore, provides an essential local reference sequence, and many of the more successful recent surveys in greater Mesopotamian have been conducted in tandem with excavation. Furthermore, some recent surveys have been undertaken as part of salvage irrigation projects where deep cuts were available to provide windows into earlier occupations as well as estimates of depths of sedimentation. The employment of more intensive methodologies, finer ceramic chronologies, and geoarchaeological controls helps address earlier criticisms concerning the lack of reliability of survey results" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=8}{Wilkinson 2000:226}) \par "It is a clich{\' }e that mound survey is synonymous with Near Eastern survey, but over the last twenty years there has been a gradual but significant shift towards the recognition of the importance of smaller sites in the archaeological record" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=8}{Wilkinson 2000:226}) \par "rd. Nevertheless, survey standards continue to be uneven. Fortunately, Adams recognized that small sites played an important role in the settlement record. Yet in spite of this focus, evidence from Ur III texts has led Piotr Steinkeller to suggest that the surveys by Adams may underrepresent the spectrum of smaller settlements, the component buildings of which were made, perhaps, from perishable materials such as reeds or palm fronds (cited in Stone, 1997, p. 22). Th" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=8}{Wilkinson 2000:226}) \par "The recognition of such settlements may eventually benefit from the application of off-site survey techniques. Although such techniques have been conducted in the Near East since at least 1974, they have yet to become part of the established repertoire of techniques." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=8}{Wilkinson 2000:226}) \par "Su" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "urprisingly, the debate concerning intensive sample survey versus fullcoverage survey continues (Kowalewski and Fish, 1990; Sumner, 1990a; cf. for example full-coverage surveys in Mesoamerica: Kowalewski, 1990; Parsons, 1990)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "In contrast to sample survey that makes generalizations about the whole by sampling only a part of the area, full-coverage survey takes as its limits the boundary of the natural region so that all significant sites are visited within the designated area. This top-down approach, which continues to be practiced almost exclusively in Mesopotamia, has the distinct advantage of providing structural patterns that can then be analyzed by spatial analysis and location models" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "On the other hand, it has the disadvantage of underrepresenting smaller sites, which can be fundamental to understanding the processes of settlement change" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "nge. I therefore advocate a combined approach for Mesopotamian archaeology in which full-coverage methods are used to recover the basic settlement structure, and sample surv" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "combined approach for Mesopotamian archaeology in which full-coverage methods are used to recover the basic settlement structure, and sample surveys" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "s (e.g., Batovic0 and Chapman, 1985) provide estimates of the distribution of site sizes, particularly those at the smaller end of the spectrum (Redman, 1973)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "provide estimates of the distribution of site sizes, particularly those at the smaller end of the spectrum (" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "The surveys of Adams were extensive operations covering very large areas, and only at a later stage was localized control initiated in the form of sample surveys of 1 km squares (Adams, 1981, p. 40). Such an extensive approach was justified because the general survey would "provide a first approximation that would speak more comprehensively to major historical and anthropological problems" (Adams and Nissen, 1972, p. 8)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "Surveys by Gibson (1972) and Wright (1969, 1981) have added further details, and more intensive operations have tested the results of the earlier surveys. For example, in the areas of Abu Salabikh and Abu Duwari, which include both cultivation and desert, mounded sites exist within a matrix of deflated desert covered by a light scatter of pottery and crossed by occasional linear upcast mounds, soil, or moisture marks of relict canals (Wilkinson, 1990a, Fig. 1). Within the low and deflated site of Abu Duwari, systematic surface collection provided a distribution of artifact classes that supplied a clearer pattern of the layout of site functions (ceramic kilns, metal working, religious quarter) than is possible on most high mounded sites in Upper Mesopotamia (Stone, 1990; Stone and Zimansky, 1994)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "Despite the early introduction of on-site sampling methodology" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "gy (see Stein and Wattenmaker, 1990, Fig. 5; Whallon, 1979), these techniques are not frequently applied. In part, this is so not only becaus" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "these techniques are not frequently applied. In part, this is so not only because of the large number of archaeological sites that must be recorded by small teams, but also because there is sometimes greater utility in spending the available time carefully evaluating the greater site area" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "(including apparent "off-site" areas) in order to determine whether subtle traces of other settlements remain in the immediate site periphery. In other wor" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "In other words, it can be more effective to recover a 10 ha lower town than to neglect such a feature and elegantly subdivide a 1- to 2-ha tell into smaller subunits that may fall between the main size classes employed in statistical analysis" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=9}{Wilkinson 2000:227}) \par "Although in recent years advances have been made in the recovery of off-site data (Wilkinson, 1982), buried sites (Banning, 1996), landscape features such as canals, and pastoral camps (Bernbeck, 1994; Hole, 1991), such contexts continue to be overlooked because the focus remains on the more visible elements of the archaeological spectrum" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "Criteria for site recognition have now been extended to include site microtopography, scatters of foundation stones, diagnostic objects such as querns, door sockets, etc., soil color, and various negative topographic features" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "Although surveyors are now well aware that more closely spaced transects are necessary to recognize smaller settlements (Neely and Wright, 1994; Redman, 1982; Wright, 1981, p. 298), considerable numbers of sites are still being missed. This is unfortunate because such sites are fundamental to the recognition of changes in settlement structure, such as one that took place in the late 2\textsuperscript{nd} and early 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium B.C. (see below)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "At a still lower level of visibility are the low-density scatters of battered sherds that extend across large areas of terrain between conventional sedentary sites and that can be related, in part, to the practice of hauling organic refuse from settlements to spread on the fields as fertilizer" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "These "field scatters" form a background noise that not only inhibits recognition of very small sites, but can alternatively provide valuable data on ancient land-use zones" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "Because of their extensive methodology, few surveys actually recognize such off-site materials, let alone make an attempt to differentiate them from true occupation sites as is virtually the norm in adjacent parts of the Mediterranean" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "In the Near East as one moves west towards the Mediterranean, it appears that small settlements were more common on the uplands, especially during the Roman and Byzantine periods. Therefore, the application of intensive survey techniques, as have long been practiced in the Mediterranean basin (cf. Cherry et al., 1991), to areas of western Syria and southern Turkey is essential in order to recover the smaller sites. Surveys also need to allow for the missing sites and landscapes, such as are now being recognized in the Levantine uplands where punctuations in the settlement record may be due to the failure to recognize buried sites in wadi floors (Banning, 1996). Similar techniques might be applicable to many of the uplands that fringe Mesopotamia." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "Earlier Mesopotamian surveys made use of air photos when they were available; satellite images" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "ges (mainly LANDSAT images with a very coarse resolution) were only just becoming available when Adams was undertaking his later sur-" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "were only just becoming available when Adams was undertaking his later surveys. Now with a wider range of available images, at different resolutions or pixel size, spectral range, and surface penetrability, major advances are being made in site recognition and mapping, especially when image analysis is conducted in tandem with detailed ground truthing by archaeological survey" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "Ironically, because they include less urban industrial clutter from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s, the earlier low-tech photographic declassified" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=10}{Wilkinson 2000:228}) \par "images are now providing a wealth of information on both sites and off-site features over vast areas of the Near East (Kennedy, 1998). This availability of high-quality Corona images is now enabling Adams and others to re-evaluate the earlier surveys of southern Mesopotamia." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=11}{Wilkinson 2000:229}) \par "That physical loss of archaeological sites occurs as a result of geomorphological landscape processes is well known (" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=11}{Wilkinson 2000:229}) \par "Thus various degrees of sedimentation have resulted in the burial of the archaeological record in the Tigris-Euphrates lowlands" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=11}{Wilkinson 2000:229}) \par "Cultural transformations are not so well documented in the Near East, but they clearly inhibit the interpretation of the settlement record. The notion of "landscapes of survival" and "landscapes of destruction" as initially recognized for Britain (Taylor, 1972) may also be applied to the Middle East. Thus settlement is rare in deserts or in many uplands, but where settlement or off-site activity did take place, their traces have a high probability of survival because there would be little subsequent activity to remove them. The desert, therefore, constitutes a landscape of survival. On the other hand, in moister areas where conditions are more conducive to sustained long-term settlement, later phases of occupation either obscure earlier traces (if they rest upon them) or effectively erase them as part of a constant process of recycling. Therefore field boundaries, ancient roads, or canals only remain if they are sufficiently robust, or as long as they continue to be of use to the inhabitants. Otherwise mud or mudbrick features may be dug away and stones recycled into other structures. As a result, as rainfall and human activities increase, other things being equal, a larger amount of the settlement and landscape record will be lost by being recycled, obscured, removed, or disturbed. This process may have resulted in the attrition of many landscape features in the more verdant parts of Upper Mesopotamia. Where later occupations are apparently more numerous than those of earlier periods it is, of course, difficult to assess to what degree earlier occupation has been lost from view. This obscuring process is not uniform, however, and in parts of the Khabur basin, Syria, for example, settlement on tells often ceased in the late 3\textsuperscript{rd} millennium B.C. with the result that the pre-Bronze Age levels are frequently obscured." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=11}{Wilkinson 2000:229}) \par "On the other hand, further west in, for example, the Amuq Plain of southern Turkey and much of western Syria, tells" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=11}{Wilkinson 2000:229}) \par "are frequently occupied until the Islamic period (e.g., Tell Judaidah and Chatal Hoyuk, Haines, 1971) with the result that a significant amount of both Bronze and Iron Age occupation will have been lost from view, and earlier prehistoric occupations may be entirely invisible." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=12}{Wilkinson 2000:230}) \par "Deurbanization in southern Mesopotamia during the mid-2\textsuperscript{nd} millennium B.C. is apparently paralleled by a similar decline in northern Mesopotamia, but detailed correlations are dependent on recent revisions of the 2\textsuperscript{nd} millennium chronology, which suggest that the commonly used middle chronology is too high by 75- 125 years (Gasche et al., 1998, p. 25). How such revisions affect the chronology of sites in the north remains to be seen." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=27}{Wilkinson 2000:245}) \par "Population shifts were pervasive in the Middle and Late Assyrian periods but especially so between the 9\textsuperscript{th} and 7\textsuperscript{th} centuries B.C. when imperial policy impelled mass transfers of populations throughout the empire. This pattern is manifested in the survey record by a considerable increase in rural settlement" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=27}{Wilkinson 2000:245}) \par "Barbanes, 1999, pp. 35-71; Wilkinson, 1995)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=27}{Wilkinson 2000:245}) \par "Defensive considerations also resulted in a substantial increase in fortified settlements and what are interpreted as temporary camps in the Haditha dam area in Iraq" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=27}{Wilkinson 2000:245}) \par "Although population" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=27}{Wilkinson 2000:245}) \par "increase in the southern alluvial plains was probably underway some time after the 8\textsuperscript{th} century B.C., the precise timing is difficult to establish. Nevertheless, through the late 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium B.C. and early 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium A.D. there was a substantial increase in population in the south so that both aggregate settlement area and the sheer scale of urban settlements were higher than at any time before. This" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=28}{Wilkinson 2000:246}) \par "his phase of settlement increase also was evident along parts of the Euphrates Valley in Syria (Geyer and Monchambert, 1987; Simpson, 1983) but the scale of southern urbanization could hardly be matched in the rain-fed north." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=28}{Wilkinson 2000:246}) \par "Survey data, although valuable as a demographic proxy indicator, should be used with caution. If the quantity of sites through time is employed as a proxy and there were many small sites, population may be overestimated; if there were a few large sites, population may be underestimated" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "Aggregate settlement area, defined here as the sum of the areas of all sites of a given phase" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "preferably displayed according to site-size class, has supplied better estimates of population than the number of sites alone; see for example (Fig. 5), the Diyala (Adams, 1965, Table 25), the alluvial plains of Iraq (Whitmore et al., 1990, based on Adams, 1981), southern Turkey (Wilkinson, 1990b), and northern Iraq" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "However, factors such as burial of sites below alluvium or later occupation levels, lack of recognition or low "visibility" of certain ceramic types, and assumptions of uniform on-site population densities [usually assumed to fall in the range 100-150 persons per ha, but see Postgate (1994) for high estimates] all serve to reduce the accuracy of estimates." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "n addition, population estimates may be inaccurate because the aggregate settlement area method assumes that all components of each ceramic phase are contemporary," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "Not only are ceramic periods usually of different lengths so that long periods may contain more sites than were actually occupied at one time, but also "within the time span during which a cultural phase existed, settlements were founded, grew, declined, and were abandoned or moved to other locations" (Dewar, in Neely and Wright, 1994, p. 200)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "adjust for both varying lengths of ceramic periods and the dynamics of settlement foundation, continuity, or extinction, probabilistic models now exist for estimating the abandonment and establishment rate of sites as well as the number of sites that continued in use through two adjacent periods (Dewar, 1991; for an early Mesopotamian application see Gibson" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=29}{Wilkinson 2000:247}) \par "For all of the above reasons, population estimates from Mesopotamian surveys may be inaccurate. Despite these potential problems in primary survey results, Dewar's methodology has been successfully applied to data from the Deh Luran Plain in western Iran, from the Choga Mami Transitional (ca. 5500 B.C.) to Early Dynastic III (ca. 2600 B.C.) (Neely and Wright, 1994, Fig. 6.1)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=31}{Wilkinson 2000:249}) \par "As an alternative to long-duration population proxy curves, spatial population (or settlement) density estimates can be made for selected periods, bearing in mind, however, the above caveats concerning the quality of the settlement record" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=31}{Wilkinson 2000:249}) \par "during the 3\textsuperscript{rd} millennium B.C., parts of the rain-fed north appear to have been occupied at a greater density than the irrigated south" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=31}{Wilkinson 2000:249}) \par "The figures for northern Mesopotamia may be biased, however, because of the concentration of population in the north around growing urban centers such as Leilan" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=31}{Wilkinson 2000:249}) \par "On the other hand, in southern Mesopotamia large areas may have remained unsettled by sedentary inhabitants in part because available water was insufficient to irrigate the entire plain" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=31}{Wilkinson 2000:249}) \par "Because this intensification coincided with a concentration of settlement and an associated desertion of neighboring regions, intensification and population pressure can be regarded as a localized phenomenon" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=32}{Wilkinson 2000:250}) \par "Any excess population could, therefore, have returned to formerly abandoned regions. On the other hand, in southern Mesopotamia in the 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium A.D., when Parthian and Sasanian irrigation systems were attaining scales never before reached and population levels on the alluvial plains were considerable, the presence of extensive field scatters suggests that manuring was being employed to enhance production" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=32}{Wilkinson 2000:250}) \par "With their perennial concerns for monumental architecture, big sites, and early complex civilizations, Near Eastern archaeologists have tended to underrepresent pastoral nomadic communities, despite the significant reference to such groups in cuneiform texts from Mari and elsewhere" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=32}{Wilkinson 2000:250}) \par "This underrepresentation is partly a result of the difficulty of recognizing such sites as well as their regrettable loss due to land degradation and modern land-use practices" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=32}{Wilkinson 2000:250}) \par "Nevertheless, some progress has been made, both in the recognition and recording of such sites, as well as their incorporation into models" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=32}{Wilkinson 2000:250}) \par "cultural development (Danti, 1997; Danti and Zettler, 1998; Geyer, 1998; Lyonnet, 1998; Sumner, 1990b; Zarins, 1990)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "Pastoral nomadic sites have now been recognized along the Khabur" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "the Wadi Ajij" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "in the eastern hinterland of Tell Sweyhat (" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "along the Turkish Euphrates" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "Often pastoral sites are located away from good cultivable land (Hole, 1991, p. 19), frequently on marginal areas where they exhibit insubstantial architectural remains" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "herd densities are low, and usually only one or two diagnostics belong to each of a wide range of archaeological periods, implying relatively short visits by ceramically impoverished visitors over long spans of time. This record contrasts with nearby rural sedentary sites that typically provide numerous diagnostic sherds belonging to only one or two periods" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "mobile communities probably played a significant role in the economy of many settlements systems by complementing the practice of rain-fed cultivation" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "Unfortunately, canals are problematic to date (Monchambert, 1990), and the few of regional scale that have been excavated, described, and dated appear to be of Hellenistic, Parthian, or later date." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "There is still nothing to dispute Adam's statement that "large-scale complex irrigation practices" were developed in the 3\textsuperscript{rd} millennium B.C. and that such systems followed the large-scale development of urban and state-level society" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "The debate on Wittfogel and the relationship between state society and the development of irrigation, although currently less vigorous than before, still continues" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=33}{Wilkinson 2000:251}) \par "Nevertheless, the best-dated and least ambiguous regional-scale canal systems are estimated to have been built in the 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium B.C. or later, and Wittfogel's arguments for relationships between hydraulic administration and system scale continue to be more appropriate to these later periods" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=34}{Wilkinson 2000:252}) \par "Although it is likely that regional-scale canal systems did exist prior to the 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium B.C., these are poorly attested with the exception of Kassite systems from the area of Uruk" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=34}{Wilkinson 2000:252}) \par "a canal near Nippur" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=34}{Wilkinson 2000:252}) \par "There is as yet, however, little well-dated excavated information to support textual and surface studies for the canal systems around sites such as Mari" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=34}{Wilkinson 2000:252}) \par "Since the 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium B.C., large regional-scale canal systems appear to have been constructed throughout 