 "Rank-size curves also continue" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=34}{Wilkinson 2000:252}) \par \emph{inferential=inferenziale= attinente a prove deducibili o generalizzazioni di dati parziali (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=34}{note on p.252})} \par "find favor as both a descriptive and analytical tool (Falconer and Savage, 1995; Savage, 1997)," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "because of their reliance on the assumption that size equals importance, the more qualitative heterarchy models are more likely to gain in importance. Certainly there is room for a new generation of spatial analyses, especially because Geographical Information Systems are now widely used for the manipulation and analysis of survey data. However, this new wave of methods will have to explore social processes and nonmoneterized economies with greater subtlety than hitherto" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "First, in Upper Mesopotamia a major transition occurred after the Early Bronze Age, from the earlier nucleated tell-based landscapes to the rural dispersed pattern of settlement, with occasional extensive towns, that was characteristic of the 1\textsuperscript{st} millennium B.C. and later." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "he former patterns can be seen to relate to citystate types of settlement systems, whereas the latter coincide with the development of territorial empires." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "Second, an overall impression gained from the numerous surveys is that there has been a considerable amount of differential population growth and shifts throughout Greater Mesopotamia," (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "some" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "etimes evident as a settlement rise in one area countered by a decline in another" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "The implication of these shifts in settlement is that there have been significant movements in population from place to place. The causes of such flux may be numerous; clearly, state-sponsored transfers are explicit in the Neo-Assyrian texts (Oded, 1979) and can be inferred from the archaeological data, but they remain difficult to pin down precisely (Oates, 1968b; Wilkinson, 1995). However, more subtle circulations were probably also operating. These would include rural to urban movements that replenished urban populations subject to decline as a result of infectious disease (McNeill, 1978, pp. 5-10) and fluxes between pastoral nomadic and sedentary communities" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "Just as marginal areas may have been settled when political and climatic conditions were propitious, abandonment of marginal areas would have taken place when such favorable conditions reversed, and episodes of drought probably resulted in stress, production shortfalls, famine, and settlement decline" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=35}{Wilkinson 2000:253}) \par "Both climatic or human factors may have contributed to settlement collapse, but solutions that polarize the debate to one extreme or other may oversimplify a more complex reality" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "reality. For example, in the rain-fed zone economies based largely upon the production of staples, mainly cereals, may have been more vulnerable to climatic fluctuations such as runs of dry years, whereas more wealthbased economies with a greater proportion of income from trade, exchange, tribute, or mineral extraction could override climatic fluctuations by buying foods, even at a high "price."" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "the other hand, the latter systems would have been vulnerable to fluctuations in political/economic conditions, in part because individuals in wealth-based systems are more likely to interact as social equivalents rather than according to existing social hierarchies" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "Settlements reliant on wealth transactions also are vulnerable to disruptions in exchange networks" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "Such differential development of political economies would, therefore, result in a patterned process of response to environmental, economic, and social stress." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "In addition, wars and related large-scale conflicts are obviously pernicious" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "As eloquently described by Abu-Lughod (1978), these events can have tremendous effects not simply on the migrants who initially suffered and fled the war zone, but also on the communities that received them. Such flight may have been towards areas where there were family or lineage links, but often many of the migrations were entirely unanticipated "surprise" events." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "Survey evidence provides information to sketch recent shifts of population, but these are only rough approximations because we usually cannot directly link a decline in one area with a rise in another." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "basin, but it is important that we do not see demographic shifts simply in terms of negative factor" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=36}{Wilkinson 2000:254}) \par "Spatial differentiation therefore appears to be an important factor in the regional archaeology of Upper Mesopotamia from at least the 3\textsuperscript{rd} millennium B.C." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=37}{Wilkinson 2000:255}) \par "On the other hand, periods of demographic devolution may result in a patterned response, collapse, ruralization, urban survival, or urban growth that partly reflects the patterning of the political economy. These various manifestations occur because political economies were not unidimensional but employed a mixture of strategies (Hirth, 1996, p. 220), some of which were more vulnerable to climatic fluctuations whereas other were vulnerable to political or economic upheavals" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=37}{Wilkinson 2000:255}) \par "Finally, we should make greater use of the rich array of textual evidence that is available and that is underutilized in regional analysis, but which can yield fundamental information on the economic and geographical infrastructure at a regional scale (Cole and Gasche, 1998; Fales, 1990; Steinkeller, 1999). Archaeological site survey is not the only way of conducting research at a regional scale." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=37}{Wilkinson 2000:255}) \par "Atlas of Archaeological Sites in Iraq (1976). Ministry of Information, Directorate General of Antiquities, Baghdad, Republic of Iraq (2 vols. in Arabic)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=38}{Wilkinson 2000:256}) \par "Banning, E. B. (1996). Highlands and lowlands: Problems and survey frameworks for rural archaeology in the Near East. Bulletin of the American Schools for Oriental Research 301: 25- 45." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=39}{Wilkinson 2000:257}) \par "Barbanes, E. (1999). Heartland and Province: Urban and Rural Settlement in the Neo-Assyrian Empire" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/ECLLPEXW?page=39}{Wilkinson 2000:257}) \par "\textasciicaron{} Bernbeck, R. (1994). Settled and mobile