  month     = jan,
  note      = {\section{\textbf{Annotazioni (15/5/2022, 15:48:37)}} \par "Behind the city to the north lie the slopes of Jebel Kassyun, part of the forbidding spine of the Anti-Lebanon" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=22}{Burns 2005:22}) \par "While the Damascus rainfall (220 mm per year4 is barely enough to sustain permanent agriculture, it is more than compensated by the precipitation stored on the snowy peaks and released into the Barada with the spring thaw." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=22}{Burns 2005:22}) \par "Even the Old Testament marvelled at the boundless flow of the Abana (Barada) in 2 Kings 5.12 - 'Surely, Abana and Parpar, the rivers of Damascus, are better than any water in Israel?" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=22}{Burns 2005:22}) \par "The stream is fed not only from the snow melt released in summer by the steep slopes but from the marshy lakes near Zabadani and by the abundant spring at \lasp Ain al-Fijeh, half way along the river's course (now largely siphoned off for the city's drinking water)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=22}{Burns 2005:22}) \par "In the beginning, before man intruded, the waters of the Barada simply rushed impetuously into the city down the confined gorge and, especially during the early summer flood, spilled onto the plain" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=23}{Burns 2005:23}) \par "The run-off either settled in low-lying swamps or evaporated through the marshes of Ateibe, east of the city. The Damascus basin drew minor supplementation from two other streams, the Mnin flowing out of the Anti-Lebanon behind Kassyun and the \lasp Awaj (the Parpar of the Old Testament quote above) which flows from Mount Hermon and gouges on its eastward course a small valley marking the southern limit of the" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=23}{Burns 2005:23}) \par "This irrigated zone extends to the east no more than 20 kilometres before the wilderness takes over. In fact, only the first ten kilometres is good agricultural land capable of bearing a full range of crops (the true Ghouta). The eastern marginal zone, al-Mardj, is a soggy meadow when the waters of the Barada reach it in the spring but only sparse pasture remains by the end of summer" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=32}{Burns 2005:32}) \par "The first landing in Damascus took place in 1912, using the meadows that still survived in the neighbourhood of the Tekkiye." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=320}{Burns 2005:320}) \par "marj grazing area on the edge of cultivated land (hence: Merdje Square). Other parts of the Damascus marj are referred to by specific names - e.g. Marj Rahit (northeast of the city - after fourteenth century, Marj al-\lasp Adra'), Marj al-Suffar (south). These areas often served as rallying zones for invading armies" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=357}{Burns 2005:357}) \par "Thoumin, R. (1936) G\'eographie humaine de la Syrie centrale, Paris: Librairie Ernest Roux" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/Y3HTF238?page=410}{Burns 2005:410})},
