@Article{Clerc2014,
  author    = {Clerc, Val{\'e}rie},
  journal   = {Built Environment},
  title     = {Informal {{Settlements}} in the {{Syrian}} {{Conflict}}: {{Urban Planning}} as a {{Weapon}}},
  year      = {2014},
  month     = mar,
  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (14/5/2022, 23:11:40)} \par "During the fi rst decade of the new millennium, urban policy in Syria, both national and local, tackled the problem of informal sett lements" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=1}{Clerc 2014:34}) \par "At the beginning of 2011 many urban policies were still in the development stage or in the process of implementation; few had reached completion." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=1}{Clerc 2014:34}) \par "evolution of the Syrian authorities' policy on informal settlements before the 'Arab Spring'." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=2}{Clerc 2014:35}) \par "The second part focuses on the evolution of the guidelines during the conflict" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=2}{Clerc 2014:35}) \par "In 2004 about 40 per cent of the population of Damascus - approximately 1.3 million" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=2}{Clerc 2014:35}) \par "of a total of 3 million - lived in informal sett lements, defi ned in Syria as 'zones of collective contravention' (man\=ateq al-moukh\=alaf\=at al-j\=amia) (Government of Syria, 2010; Clerc, 2014). These zones developed mainly after the 1970s and 1980s, because tools available for urban planning were inadequate (al-Baridi, 2005), urbanization and population growth were rapid, rural exodus was speeding up, and waves of displaced people and refugees from regional confl icts (Palestinians, inhabitants of Golan, Iraqis) were arriving (Dora\"i, 2009)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=2}{Clerc 2014:35}) \par "In Syria informal sett lements are a lot like formal sett lements physically, socially and functionally" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=2}{Clerc 2014:35}) \par "Thanks to the policy of integration, equipment and upgrading (though not necessarily legalization) applied mainly during the 1980s and 1990s (Sakkal, 1998; al-Baridi, 2005), informal neighbourhoods are served to a large extent by public infrastructure on a normal legal basis. During the 2000s, the government continued implementing its equipment plans, putt ing in service infrastructure (schools, healthcare centres, etc.). In 2004 some 97 per cent of the informal neighbourhoods in Damascus had running water; rubbish was collected, and most streets were tarred" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=2}{Clerc 2014:35}) \par "And urban poverty was by no means confined to the informal zones (al-Laithy and Abu-Ismail, 2005). Many of the inhabitants were not recent rural migrants or refugees, and had lived in the city for a long time - sometimes for several decades - in formal or informal housing" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=3}{Clerc 2014:36}) \par "Despite all these continuities, however, Syrian informal neighbourhoods were nonetheless distinguished by their urban" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=3}{Clerc 2014:36}) \par "ology and land tenure, as well as their national legal definition" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=3}{Clerc 2014:36}) \par "There were two main types of land tenure: some settlements had developed on land that had been squatted by the initial occupants - this was mainly the case with public land and zones on the slopes of Mount Qassioun (illegal construction plus illegal occupation of land) - and other settlements built on privatelyowned land which, though legally held by its occupants, were areas where building was not permitted" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=3}{Clerc 2014:36}) \par "This latter type of occupation was mainly to be found in the Ghouta" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=3}{Clerc 2014:36}) \par "They constituted homogeneous urban spaces that had been organized gradually as the inhabitants moved in, with hierarchies of streets and processes of densification similar to those described in the nineteenth century in the suburbs of Damascus (Lena, 2012; Arnaud, 2006); plots were small and streets narrow, adjoining buildings were not set back from the street, and buildings were usually low" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=3}{Clerc 2014:36}) \par "net density of occupation was often two or three times that of the urban area as a whole, and up to 1200 inhabitants per hectare, compared with 260 in the urban area as a whole (Central Bureau of Statistics, 2004)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=4}{Clerc 2014:37}) \par "As the Syrian economy opened up, gathering speed after Bachar el-Assad came to power in 2000, and again in 2005 when the social market economy model was adopted to restore equilibrium between the social and economic facets of development, new urban policies were adopted with a dual aim: that of liberalizing the economy while, at the same time, maintaining a safetynet of social protection" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=4}{Clerc 2014:37}) \par "By 2007, the annual production of housing units in the metropolitan area had been multiplied by seven, and in the suburbs of the capital by fifteen" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=4}{Clerc 2014:37}) \par "A new law in 2003 required the destruction of all buildings that infringed regulations (and in 2008 stipulated stiff prison sentences for persons involved in any way in the building operations); but on the other hand it also enabled the legalization of neighbourhoods built before this date, on condition that the existing buildings were compatible with the local master plan; this however was usually not the case" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=5}{Clerc 2014:38}) \par "From the outset of the uprising, illegal construction began to boom: numerous infringements took place in the formal zones while in informal zones construction soared" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=8}{Clerc 2014:41}) \par "After some months local urban planners who were interviewed estimated the rate of increase at about 10 per cent in Damascus, basing this fi gure on visits to the terrains and on photos" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=8}{Clerc 2014:41}) \par "As international cooperation programmes with Western countries came to a halt in 2011, Syria explored ways to reactivate cooperation with Iran in the fields of construction, housing and urban planning" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=9}{Clerc 2014:42}) \par "proFigure 4. Illegal construction began to boom from the very outset of the uprising in 2011, and continued in 2012, as illustrated here on the satellite images of a plot located in Douma (Rif Damascus). (Source: @Google Earth, snapshots of 9 November 2009, 5 May 2011 and 3 May 2012)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=9}{Clerc 2014:42}) \par "neighbourand to benefit from Iranian expertise in these fields.4" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=10}{Clerc 2014:43}) \par "On the other hand, the authorities used urban planning as a weapon, not only by destroying opponents' houses and bombarding the quarters held by the armed opposition, but also by drawing up projects for urban renewal" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=11}{Clerc 2014:44}) \par "demolition and reconstruction) of specifi c neighbourhoods" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=11}{Clerc 2014:44}) \par "And in May 2013 the United Nations, working through the UN Economic Commission for Western Asia (ESCWA), estimated that almost a third of housing units, i.e. 1.2 million, had been affected by the conflict" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=11}{Clerc 2014:44}) \par "Premises left vacant were in some cases partially or completely destroyed, but often they were simply rented out, occupied illegally, rented out or sold by persons other than the legal owners, or in some cases even sold simultaneously to several different persons (Hassan, 2012). Most destruction of housing apparently took place in the informal parts of zones affected by the conflict, near the principal cities: Homs, Damascus, Aleppo, Daraa and Deir ez-Zor.16 Around Damascus, East Ghouta and the informal settlements to the south and southeast seem to be those most affected" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=11}{Clerc 2014:44}) \par "On the other hand, however, and whatever the parties to the conflict, destruction is used against adversaries: buildings are destroyed, and even entire neighbourhoods were bombarded and/or wiped out to get rid of combatants and their possible supporters, or simply to gain control of strategic positions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=12}{Clerc 2014:45}) \par "Moreover, urban planning and laws towards informal settlements are used as a weapon in the conflict" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=12}{Clerc 2014:45}) \par "Satellite imagery showed approximately 1,000 structures destroyed [see fi gure 5]. [The informal neighbourhood of] Qaboon, north of Damascus (October), experienced the same... The Government justifi ed the above-mentioned demolitions as (there were allegedly) pre-existing urban plans to remove illegal buildings. (United Nations General Assembly, 2013, p. 23)" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=13}{Clerc 2014:46}) \par "Plans and projects were now transformed into arguments - and even weapons - in favour of, or to actually bring about the lawful demolition of entire neighbourhoods" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=13}{Clerc 2014:46}) \par "Before the demonstrations broke out, there was already competition between two types of urban policy concerning informal sett lements in Damascus: renewal and upgrading. The beginnings of the uprising and the political crisis in Syria led the authorities to modify their stance, as they aimed at creating the illusion that despite the agitation, things were still quite normal. However, they subsequently used urban policies to bolster the regime. In the early stages, this led the Governorate of Damascus to prioritize the option that was most acceptable from a social point of view: upgrading." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=14}{Clerc 2014:47}) \par "Arnaud J.-L. (2006) Damas, urbanisme et architecture. 1860-1925. Paris: Actes Sud, Sindbad" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=16}{Clerc 2014:49}) \par "Fernandes, E. (2008) Informal sett lements in Syria: A General Framework for Understanding and Confronting the Phenomenon. Damascus: European Union Municipal Administration Modernization (MAM) Project" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/9AKEBFCU?page=17}{Clerc 2014:50})},
  number    = {1},
