otero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=196}{Haddad 2009:549}) \par "of public space and public realm became more dominant" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=197}{Haddad 2009:550}) \par "The arrival of French functionaries and soldiers with their families accelerated the development of the districts located along the road connecting Salihiyye, Foud Street and Saroudja district to form a new square" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=197}{Haddad 2009:550}) \par "In brief, public space and public realm experienced main changes during the period from 1800 up to independence. The main characteristic of these changes is the increase in 'publicness' of public spaces. This was in forming new centres accommodated administrative, governmental and cultural uses and took the shape of blocks and straight streets." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=201}{Haddad 2009:554}) \par "5.2.4 Post independence up to the present day" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=202}{Haddad 2009:555}) \par "Three periods of change could be identified within the whole period. These are: the early independence years, the Socialist period of the 1970s, and the transition period of the 1990s." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=202}{Haddad 2009:555}) \par "The authorities commissioned a Bulgarian expert, Morozov, to propose a new master plan in 1957 with an emphasis on resolving inner-city problems in a typically modernist way: i.e. through large-scale clearances. But the plan was rejected because it raised very negative reactions from a consultant body of professional who saw that the plan contradicted the nature of the historic fabric, where houses were inward-looking into interior courtyards, turning their backs on the public domain of the street" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/GZUREU8T?page=203}{Haddad 2009:556}) \par "The authorities called upon Ecochard and Benshoya in 1964 to prepare a new mast