@Article{Reilly1989,
  author    = {Reilly, James A.},
  journal   = {International Journal of Middle East Studies},
  title     = {Status {{Groups}} and {{Propertyholding}} in the {{Damascus Hinterland}}, 1828-1880},
  year      = {1989},
  issn      = {0020-7438},
  note      = {\textbf{Annotazioni Estratte (15/5/2022, 15:51:02)} \par "There is a basic distinction in Syria between rain-fed and irrigated areas with respect to land tenure and agriculture. Damascus is a case in point. The city receives no more rainfall than does a semiarid steppe, but because of the Barada River it has historically been associated with irrigated farming" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=1}{Reilly 1989:517}) \par "Erratic autumn and spring rains are the most critical for rain-fed agriculture. Autumn rains soften the soil for ploughing and assure normal germination of winter cereals. Spring rains can compensate for meager autumn and winter rains, and they coincide with the flowering of fruit trees and the earing of cereals. Irrigated agriculture, on the other hand, can count on the perennial waters of the Barada." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=1}{Reilly 1989:517}) \par "permitting summer irrigation, the Barada is helpful during the autumn and spring sowing seasons. Peasants in the Ghuta (the oasis of Damascus) combine rainfall with irrigation, planting seeds with the autumn rains and then irrigating them with the Barada to hasten germination.5" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=2}{Reilly 1989:518}) \par "This difference in the availability of water conditioned the historical development of land-tenure patterns in the irrigated Ghuta and on the plains." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=2}{Reilly 1989:518}) \par "In addition to being privately held and worked by tenants, land in the Ghuta was divided into small-scale parcels, unlike the large estates that were common in the Marj (a cultivated plain east of the Ghuta) and the Horns and Hama plains in central Syria." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=2}{Reilly 1989:518}) \par "The Ghuta's small scale of landholdings was related to the intensive nature of its agriculture. Each parcel demanded sustained individual attention. Although townspeople owned Ghuta lands, their holdings were usually neither large nor even contiguous. Small peasant proprietorship was more prevalent in the Ghuta than in many other parts of Syria, at least in the last two centuries.9 Water rights were as meticulously apportioned as land rights, with all landholders having the claim to a share" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=2}{Reilly 1989:518}) \par "Properties whose agriculture depended primarily or exclusively on perennial irrigation were located in the Ghuta, the Barada valley to the northwest, and the al-cAjam valley to the south." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=2}{Reilly 1989:518}) \par "Regions of extensive agriculture (mostly grain) that depended primarily (but not exclusively) on rainfall were located in the" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=2}{Reilly 1989:518}) \par "Marj to the east, the Bekaa valley to the west, the Hawran to the south, and the Golan to the southwest" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=3}{Reilly 1989:519}) \par "Rather than second-guess the registers and stray too far from the source material, the author has preferred to categorize people as the 19\textsuperscript{th}-century scribes did" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=3}{Reilly 1989:519}) \par "Most officials' land acquisitions were in irrigated regions. This preponderance is to be expected, since irrigated lands were more valuable and productive than rain-fed lands, and since the irrigated lands were divided into small parcels14 (thereby contributing to frequency of purchase or lease). But the percentage of rain-fed lands bought or leased by officials is significant, particularly when compared to corresponding figures for the bulk of the townspeople (presented later in Table 6). Officials predominated in the acquisition of rain-fed lands in the plains, where they obtained legal control over entire villages or percentages thereof. Rich estates were located in the irrigated Ghuta, but large estates (also lucrative) were found in the rain-fed plains." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=4}{Reilly 1989:520}) \par "With the Egyptian regime and its Tanzimat-era Ottoman successor, however, the role of the sharifs and ulama in agricultural and rural propertyholding became modest. With one exception (the 1879 sample), the value of their purchases was less than the overall average. Moreover, by the 1850s, when commercialization of Syrian agriculture was proceeding apace and persons with access to rain-fed, graingrowing lands were profiting as a result of Anglo-French purchases to provision their Crimean armies, the sharifs and ulama were being economically marginalized by their concentration on exclusively acquiring properties in irrigated lands close to Damascus. (3) Although the role of the sharifs and ulama in the agricultural economy of the wider Damascus region was apparently being reduced, they nevertheless remained prominent in the traditional market garden agriculture of the Damascus oasis" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=5}{Reilly 1989:521}) \par "For the most part, the townspeople did not possess the amounts of wealth enjoyed by officials and some ulama. Table 6 shows that, with rare exceptions, townspeople's acquisitions were restricted to the irrigated regions immediately around Damascus. Ownership of large estates in rain-fed areas\textemdash including the ownership of entire villages\textemdash was virtually monopolized by those in official circles, implying that government connections were necessary to obtain and administer them." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=6}{Reilly 1989:522}) \par "When Christians and Jews acquired rural properties, their holdings were restricted to the irrigated villages of the Ghuta and the Barada and al-cAjam valleys. No evidence can be found in the registers of Christians or Jews purchasing or leasing farms, estates, and villages'in grain-growing regions such as the Bekaa, Marj, and Hawran, transactions in which figured officials, officers, and occasionally ulama." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=7}{Reilly 1989:523}) \par "With one exception (in 1859-1860), all properties purchased by villagers were in irrigated areas. This distribution underscores the following: (1) the existence of clearly defined individual property rights for cultivators in the irrigated regions; (2) the apparent absence of such individual (as opposed to family or village) property rights in rain-fed regions; and (3) the vulnerability (because of the lack of firm individual title) of villages in rain-fed regions to becoming the exclusive property of one or a number of urbanites. The lopsided geographic distribution of villagers' purchases, therefore, suggests that large estates (and weak peasant proprietary rights) were characteristic more of rain-fed areas than of irrigated regions." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=8}{Reilly 1989:524}) \par "The properties in all these cases were located in irrigated regions. Proteges' purchases were only a small proportion of the total that were registered in Damascus in any given year. The fact that all of the foreign buyers were Jewish and Christian proteges of European powers demonstrates that direct European economic influence on the agricultural economy of Damascus was exercised through the protege community, not through resident Europeans." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=9}{Reilly 1989:525}) \par "The types of properties purchased by the proteges were plots and plantations in the environs of the city, including the Barada valley; but these plots were not comparable in extent to the estates that government officials acquired in regions of extensive agriculture." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=9}{Reilly 1989:525}) \par "During the period under study, the Ottoman Land Code of 1858 was promulgated and the tapu system of land registration was introduced under its auspices. But despite the prominence of the code in the historiography of the 19\textsuperscript{th} century, it appears not to have altered the underlying patterns of landholding in the Damascus region." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=12}{Reilly 1989:528}) \par "In the predominantly rain-fed, grain-growing lands of Damascus's plains, a pattern had emerged well before 1858 in which urban elites all but monopolized ownership or possession of these waqf and miri lands" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=13}{Reilly 1989:529}) \par "The coexistence of the tapu system with the sharica court system of registration suggests that the introduction of the former changed only the formalities of land registration, and that the tapu system in Damascus's irrigated lands simply replicated the older patterns of land tenure" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=13}{Reilly 1989:529}) \par "Although present, large estates did not become the norm in the Ghuta" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=13}{Reilly 1989:529}) \par "This argument does not deny that the 1858 Land Code sometimes had the consequences often attributed to it\textemdash estate formation and dispossession of cultivators. The point is merely that these consequences cannot be generalized for all the Arab provinces, and Gerber's contention that the code had differential effects is supported by the Damascus case" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=14}{Reilly 1989:530}) \par "First, acquisition of properties in the rain-fed regions of extensive agriculture\textemdash i.e., the grain-growing regions of the Marj, Hawran, Golan and the Bekaa valley\textemdash was virtually monopolized by Ottoman officials and military officers, of whom most of the latter were permanently settled in Damascus" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=14}{Reilly 1989:530}) \par "These officials and officers also bought into regions of irrigated, intensive agriculture closer to the city. Officials and officers made some of the largest individual purchases recorded. Access to large amounts of productive lands and their surpluses were characteristic of the "professional Ottomans" in Damascus" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=14}{Reilly 1989:530}) \par "The irrigated, market garden properties around the city attracted purchasers from among the ulama, who appear to have been important in this aspect of the local economy, and Muslim townspeople associated with the city's broad middle class" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=14}{Reilly 1989:530}) \par "Villagers were able to assert proprietary rights only in the irrigated regions of long-standing intensive agriculture. Individual property rights in these regionsincluding rights to shares of collective property\textemdash were recognized by the Damascus law courts." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/library/items/JU743VLQ?page=14}{Reilly 1989:530})},
