  issn     = {0021-8723},
  month    = sep,
  number   = {2},
  pages    = {560--562},
  volume   = {107},
  abstract = {Archaeology has a history of working with computation and digital technology that stretches back more than sixty years. While there are several examples from the late 1960s, including George L. Cowgill's “Computer Applications in Archaeology” (in Computers and the Humanities, Sept. 1967, pp. 17–23), one of the best known comes courtesy of James Deetz's seminal work on Arikara ceramics carried out earlier in the decade. Deetz, who is widely considered to be a father of historical archaeology, wrote a program for the MIT Computational Psycholinguistics Laboratory's IBM 704 mainframe to analyze over two thousand rim sherds from the Medicine Crow site in South Dakota to discover “stylistic coherence.” (James Deetz, Dynamics of Stylistic Change, 1965). While Deetz's research focused on the effect of social change on ceramic production, his computational work, and the work of those who followed him, such as Cowgill, Maria Asher, and Robert Asher, foreshadowed modern archaeological informatics and data science. Despite its pioneering nature, much of this early digital archaeology work faced significant hurdles: (1) despite the claims of major computer manufacturers, hardware and software were barely adequate for dealing with archaeological information; (2) facilities to support these sorts of undertakings were exceedingly rare; and (3) no consensus existed among archaeologists as to what types of data should be stored and how that data should be collected.},
  doi      = {10.1093/jahist/jaaa334},
  groups   = {ArcheoFOSS2023},
